# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: molecular-biology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The **central dogma of molecular biology** deals with the flow of genetic information within a biological system.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] It is often stated as "DNA makes RNA, and RNA makes protein", although this is not its original meaning.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] He re-stated it in a *Nature* paper published in 1970: "The central dogma of molecular biology deals with the detailed residue-by-residue transfer of sequential information.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] A second version of the central dogma is popular but incorrect.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] This is the simplistic DNA → RNA → protein pathway published by James Watson in the first edition of *The Molecular Biology of the Gene* (1965).
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Watson's version differs from Crick's because Watson describes a two-step (DNA → RNA / RNA → protein) process as the central dogma.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] While the dogma as originally stated by Crick remains valid today, Watson's version does not.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The biopolymers that comprise DNA, RNA, and (poly)peptides are linear heteropolymers (i.e.: each monomer is connected to at most two other monomers).
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The sequences of their monomers effectively encodes information.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The transfers of information from one molecule to another are faithful, deterministic transfers, wherein one biopolymer's sequence is used as a template for the construction of another biopolymer with a sequence that is entirely dependent on the original biopolymer's sequence.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] When DNA is transcribed to RNA, its complement is paired to it.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] DNA codes are transferred to RNA codes in a complementary fashion.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The encoding of proteins is done in groups of three, known as codons.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The standard codon table applies for humans and mammals, but some other lifeforms (including human mitochondria) use different translations.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] In the sense that DNA replication must occur if genetic material is to be provided for the progeny of any cell, whether somatic or reproductive, the copying from DNA to DNA arguably is the fundamental step in information transfer.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] A complex group of proteins called the replisome performs the replication of the information from the parent strand to the complementary daughter strand.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Transcription is the process by which the information contained in a section of DNA is replicated in the form of a newly assembled piece of messenger RNA (mRNA).
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Enzymes facilitating the process include RNA polymerase and transcription factors.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] In eukaryotic cells, the primary transcript is pre-mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Pre-mRNA must be processed for translation to proceed.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Processing includes the addition of a 5' cap and a poly-A tail to the pre-mRNA chain, followed by splicing.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Alternative splicing occurs when appropriate, increasing the diversity of the proteins that any single mRNA can produce.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The product of the entire transcription process (that began with the production of the pre-mRNA chain) is a mature mRNA chain.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The mature mRNA finds its way to a ribosome, where it gets translated.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] In prokaryotic cells, which have no nuclear compartment, the processes of transcription and translation may be linked together without clear separation.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] In eukaryotic cells, the site of transcription (the cell nucleus) is usually separated from the site of translation (the cytoplasm), so the mRNA must be transported out of the nucleus into the cytoplasm, where it can be bound by ribosomes.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The ribosome reads the mRNA triplet codons, usually beginning with an AUG (adenine−uracil−guanine), or initiator methionine codon downstream of the ribosome binding site.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Complexes of initiation factors and elongation factors bring aminoacylated transfer RNAs (tRNAs) into the ribosome-mRNA complex, matching the codon in the mRNA to the anti-codon on the tRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Each tRNA bears the appropriate amino acid residue to add to the polypeptide chain being synthesised.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] As the amino acids get linked into the growing peptide chain, the chain begins folding into the correct conformation.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Translation ends with a stop codon which may be a UAA, UGA, or UAG triplet.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The mRNA does not contain all the information for specifying the nature of the mature protein.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The nascent polypeptide chain released from the ribosome commonly requires additional processing before the final product emerges.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] For one thing, the correct folding process is complex and vitally important.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] For most proteins it requires other chaperone proteins to control the form of the product.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Some proteins then excise internal segments from their own peptide chains, splicing the free ends that border the gap; in such processes the inside "discarded" sections are called inteins.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Other proteins must be split into multiple sections without splicing.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Some polypeptide chains need to be cross-linked, and others must be attached to cofactors such as haem (heme) before they become functional.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Reverse transcription is the transfer of information from RNA to DNA (the reverse of normal transcription).
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] This is known to occur in the case of retroviruses, such as HIV, as well as in eukaryotes, in the case of retrotransposons and telomere synthesis.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] It is the process by which genetic information from RNA gets transcribed into new DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The family of enzymes involved in this process is called Reverse Transcriptase.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] RNA replication is the copying of one RNA to another.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The enzymes that copy RNA to new RNA, called RNA-dependent RNA polymerases, are also found in many eukaryotes, where they are involved in RNA silencing.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] RNA editing, in which an RNA sequence is altered by a complex of proteins and a "guide RNA", could also be seen as an RNA-to-RNA transfer.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The central dogma of molecular biology states that, once sequential information has passed from nucleic acid to protein, it cannot flow back from protein to nucleic acid.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Some people believe that the following activities conflict with the central dogma.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] After protein amino-acid sequences have been translated from nucleic acid chains, they can be edited by appropriate enzymes.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] This is a form of protein affecting protein sequence, not protein transferring information to nucleic acid.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Some proteins are synthesized by **nonribosomal peptide synthetases**, which can be big protein complexes, each specializing in synthesizing only one type of peptide.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Nonribosomal peptides often have cyclic or branched structures and can contain non-proteinogenic amino acids – both of these factors differentiate them from ribosome synthesized proteins.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] An example of nonribosomal peptides are some of the antibiotics.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] An intein is a "parasitic" segment of a protein that is able to excise itself from the chain of amino acids as they emerge from the ribosome and rejoin the remaining portions with a peptide bond in such a manner that the main protein "backbone" does not fall apart.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] This is a case of a protein changing its own primary sequence from the sequence originally encoded by the DNA of a gene.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Additionally, most inteins contain a homing endonuclease or HEG domain, which is capable of finding a copy of the parent gene that does not include the intein nucleotide sequence.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] On contact with the intein-free copy, the HEG domain initiates the DNA double-stranded break repair mechanism.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] This process causes the intein sequence to be copied from the original source gene to the intein-free gene.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] This is an example of protein directly editing DNA sequence, as well as increasing the sequence's heritable propagation.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Prions are proteins of particular amino acid sequences in particular conformations.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] They propagate themselves in host cells by making conformational changes in other molecules of protein with the same amino acid sequence, but with a different conformation that is functionally important or detrimental to the organism.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Once the protein has been transconformed to the prion folding, it changes function.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] In turn, it can convey information into new cells and reconfigure more functional molecules of that sequence into the alternate prion form.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] In some types of prion in fungi, this change is continuous and direct; the information flow is Protein → Protein.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Bussard and Eugene Koonin have argued that prion-mediated inheritance violates the central dogma of molecular biology.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] The Weismann barrier, proposed by August Weismann in 1892, distinguishes between the "immortal" germ cell lineages (the germ plasm) which produce gametes and the "disposable" somatic cells.
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] Hereditary information moves only from germline cells to somatic cells (that is, somatic mutations are not inherited).
[src:molecular-biology/central-dogma-of-molecular-biology] This, before the discovery of the role or structure of DNA, does not predict the central dogma, but does anticipate its gene-centric view of life, albeit in non-molecular terms.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] DNA most commonly occurs in double-stranded form, made up of two complementary strands held together by base pairing of the nucleotides comprising each strand.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The two linear strands of a double-stranded DNA molecule typically twist together in the shape of a double helix.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] During replication, the two strands are separated, and each strand of the original DNA molecule then serves as a template for the production of a complementary counterpart strand, a process referred to as semiconservative replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] As a result, each replicated DNA molecule is composed of one original DNA strand as well as one newly synthesized strand.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Cellular proofreading and error-checking mechanisms ensure near-perfect fidelity for DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] DNA replication usually begins at specific locations known as origins of replication which are scattered across the genome.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Unwinding of DNA at the origin is accommodated by enzymes known as helicases and results in replication forks growing bi-directionally from the origin.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Numerous proteins are associated with the replication fork to help in the initiation and continuation of DNA synthesis.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Most prominently, DNA polymerase synthesizes the new strands by incorporating nucleotides that complement the nucleotides of the template strand.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] DNA replication occurs during the S (synthesis) stage of interphase.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] DNA replication can also be performed *in vitro* (artificially, outside a cell).
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] DNA polymerases isolated from cells and artificial DNA primers can be used to start DNA synthesis at known sequences in a template DNA molecule.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Polymerase chain reaction (PCR), ligase chain reaction (LCR), and transcription-mediated amplification (TMA) are all common examples of this technique.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] DNA is a double-stranded structure, with both strands coiled together to form the characteristic double helix.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Each single strand of DNA is a chain of four types of nucleotides.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Nucleotides in DNA contain a deoxyribose sugar, a phosphate, and a nucleobase.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The four types of nucleotide correspond to the four nucleobases: adenine, cytosine, guanine, and thymine, commonly abbreviated as A, C, G, and T, respectively.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Adenine and guanine are purine nucleobases, while cytosine and thymine are pyrimidines.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] These nucleotides form phosphodiester bonds, creating phosphate-deoxyribose backbone of the DNA double helix with the nucleobases pointing inward (i.e., toward the opposing strand).
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Complementary nucleobases are matched between strands through hydrogen bonds to form base pairs.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Adenine pairs with thymine (two hydrogen bonds), and guanine pairs with cytosine (three hydrogen bonds).
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] DNA strands have a directionality, and the different ends of a single strand are called the "3′ (three-prime) end" and the "5′ (five-prime) end".
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] By convention, if the base sequence of a single strand of DNA is given, the left end of the sequence is the 5′ end, while the right end of the sequence is the 3′ end.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The strands of the double helix are anti-parallel, with one being 5′ to 3′, and the opposite strand 3′ to 5′.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] These terms refer to the chemical convention of numbering the carbon atoms comprising the deoxyribose molecule and indicate the specific carbon atom to which the next phosphate in the chain attaches.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Directionality has consequences in DNA synthesis, because DNA polymerase can synthesize DNA in only one direction by adding nucleotides to the 3′ end of a DNA strand.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The pairing of complementary bases in DNA (through hydrogen bonding) means that the information contained within each strand is redundant.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Phosphodiester (intra-strand) bonds are stronger than hydrogen (inter-strand) bonds.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The actual job of the phosphodiester bonds is to connect the 5' carbon atom of one nucleotide to the 3' carbon atom of another nucleotide, while the hydrogen bonds stabilize DNA double helices across the helix axis but not in the direction of the longitudinal axis.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] This makes it possible to separate the strands from one another.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The nucleotides on a single strand can therefore be used to reconstruct nucleotides on a newly synthesized partner strand.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] DNA polymerases are a family of enzymes that carry out all forms of DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] DNA polymerases in general cannot initiate synthesis of new strands but can only extend an existing DNA or RNA strand paired with a template strand.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] To begin synthesis, a short fragment of RNA, called a primer, must be created and paired with the template DNA strand.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] DNA polymerase adds a new strand of DNA by extending the 3′ end of an existing nucleotide chain, adding new nucleotides matched to the template strand, one at a time, via the creation of phosphodiester bonds.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The energy for this process of DNA polymerization comes from hydrolysis of the high-energy phosphate (phosphoanhydride) bonds between the three phosphates attached to each unincorporated base.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Free bases with an attached sugar molecule (deoxyribose in the case of DNA) are called nucleosides, and nucleosides with one or more attached phosphate groups are called nucleotides; in particular, nucleosides with three attached phosphate groups are called nucleoside triphosphates.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Enzymatic hydrolysis of the resulting pyrophosphate into inorganic phosphate consumes a second high-energy phosphate bond and renders the reaction effectively irreversible.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In general, DNA polymerases are highly accurate, with an intrinsic error rate of less than one mistake for every 107 nucleotides added.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Some DNA polymerases can also delete nucleotides from the end of a developing strand in order to fix mismatched bases.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Finally, post-replication mismatch repair mechanisms monitor the DNA for errors, being capable of distinguishing mismatches in the newly synthesized DNA strand from the original strand sequence.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Together, these three discrimination steps enable replication fidelity of less than one mistake for every 109 nucleotides added.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The rate of DNA replication in a living cell was first measured as the rate of phage T4 DNA elongation in phage-infected *E. coli*.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] During the period of exponential DNA increase at 37 °C, the rate was 749 nucleotides per second.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The mutation rate per base pair per replication during phage T4 DNA synthesis is 1.7 per 108.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] DNA replication, like all biological polymerization processes, proceeds in three enzymatically catalyzed and coordinated steps: initiation, elongation and termination.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] For a cell to divide, it must first replicate its DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] DNA replication is an all-or-none process; once replication begins, it proceeds to completion.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Once replication is complete, it does not occur again in the same cell cycle.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] This is made possible by the division of initiation of the pre-replication complex.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In late mitosis and early G1 phase, a large complex of initiator proteins assembles into the pre-replication complex at particular points in the DNA, known as "origins".
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In *E. coli* the primary initiator protein is Dna A; in yeast, this is the origin recognition complex.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Sequences used by initiator proteins tend to be "AT-rich" (rich in adenine and thymine bases), because A-T base pairs have two hydrogen bonds (rather than the three formed in a C-G pair) and thus are easier to strand-separate.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In eukaryotes, the origin recognition complex (ORC) catalyzes the assembly of initiator proteins into the pre-replication complex.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In addition, a recent report suggests that budding yeast ORC dimerizes in a cell cycle dependent manner to control licensing.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In turn, the process of ORC dimerization is mediated by a cell cycle-dependent Noc3p dimerization cycle in vivo, and this role of Noc3p is separable from its role in ribosome biogenesis.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] An essential Noc3p dimerization cycle mediates ORC double-hexamer formation in replication licensing and Noc3p are continuously bound to the chromatin throughout the cell cycle.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Cdc6 and Cdt1 then associate with the bound origin recognition complex at the origin in order to form a larger complex necessary to load the Mcm complex onto the DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In eukaryotes, the Mcm complex is the helicase that will split the DNA helix at the replication forks and origins.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The Mcm complex is recruited at late G1 phase and loaded by the ORC-Cdc6-Cdt1 complex onto the DNA via ATP-dependent protein remodeling.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The loading of the MCM complex onto the origin DNA marks the completion of pre-replication complex formation.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] If environmental conditions are right in late G1 phase, the G1 and G1/S cyclin-Cdk complexes are activated, which stimulate expression of genes that encode components of the DNA synthetic machinery.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] G1/S-Cdk activation also promotes the expression and activation of S-Cdk complexes, which may play a role in activating replication origins depending on species and cell type.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Control of these Cdks vary depending on cell type and stage of development.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] This regulation is best understood in budding yeast, where the S cyclins Clb5 and Clb6 are primarily responsible for DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Clb5,6-Cdk1 complexes directly trigger the activation of replication origins and are therefore required throughout S phase to directly activate each origin.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In a similar manner, Cdc7 is also required through S phase to activate replication origins.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Cdc7 is not active throughout the cell cycle, and its activation is strictly timed to avoid premature initiation of DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In late G1, Cdc7 activity rises abruptly as a result of association with the regulatory subunit DBF4, which binds Cdc7 directly and promotes its protein kinase activity.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Cdc7 has been found to be a rate-limiting regulator of origin activity.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Together, the G1/S-Cdks and/or S-Cdks and Cdc7 collaborate to directly activate the replication origins, leading to initiation of DNA synthesis.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In early S phase, S-Cdk and Cdc7 activation lead to the assembly of the preinitiation complex, a massive protein complex formed at the origin.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Formation of the preinitiation complex displaces Cdc6 and Cdt1 from the origin replication complex, inactivating and disassembling the pre-replication complex.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Loading the preinitiation complex onto the origin activates the Mcm helicase, causing unwinding of the DNA helix.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The preinitiation complex also loads α-primase and other DNA polymerases onto the DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] After α-primase synthesizes the first primers, the primer-template junctions interact with the clamp loader, which loads the sliding clamp onto the DNA to begin DNA synthesis.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The components of the preinitiation complex remain associated with replication forks as they move out from the origin.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] All known DNA replication systems require a free 3′ hydroxyl group before synthesis can be initiated (note: the DNA template is read in 3′ to 5′ direction whereas a new strand is synthesized in the 5′ to 3′ direction—this is often confused).
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The retroelements (including retroviruses) employ a transfer RNA that primes DNA replication by providing a free 3′ OH that is used for elongation by the reverse transcriptase.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In the adenoviruses and the φ29 family of bacteriophages, the 3′ OH group is provided by the side chain of an amino acid of the genome attached protein (the terminal protein) to which nucleotides are added by the DNA polymerase to form a new strand.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The 5′ end of the nicked strand is transferred to a tyrosine residue on the nuclease and the free 3′ OH group is then used by the DNA polymerase to synthesize the new strand.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Cellular organisms use the first of these pathways leading to it being the most well-known.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In this mechanism, once the two strands are separated, primase adds RNA primers to the template strands.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The leading strand receives one RNA primer while the lagging strand receives several.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The leading strand is continuously extended from the primer by a DNA polymerase with high processivity, while the lagging strand is extended discontinuously from each primer forming Okazaki fragments.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] RNase removes the primer RNA fragments, and a low processivity DNA polymerase distinct from the replicative polymerase enters to fill the gaps.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] When this is complete, a single nick on the leading strand and several nicks on the lagging strand can be found.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Ligase works to fill these nicks in, thus completing the newly replicated DNA molecule.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The primase used in this process differs significantly between bacteria and archaea/eukaryotes.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Bacteria use a primase belonging to the DnaG protein superfamily which contains a catalytic domain of the TOPRIM fold type.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The TOPRIM fold contains an α/β core with four conserved strands in a Rossmann-like topology.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] This structure is also found in the catalytic domains of topoisomerase Ia, topoisomerase II, the OLD-family nucleases and DNA repair proteins related to the RecR protein.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The primase used by archaea and eukaryotes, in contrast, contains a highly derived version of the RNA recognition motif (RRM).
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] This primase is structurally similar to many viral RNA-dependent RNA polymerases, reverse transcriptases, cyclic nucleotide generating cyclases and DNA polymerases of the A/B/Y families that are involved in DNA replication and repair.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In eukaryotic replication, the primase forms a complex with Pol α.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Multiple DNA polymerases take on different roles in the DNA replication process.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In *E. coli*, DNA Pol III is the polymerase enzyme primarily responsible for DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] It assembles into a replication complex at the replication fork that exhibits extremely high processivity, remaining intact for the entire replication cycle.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In contrast, DNA Pol I is the enzyme responsible for replacing RNA primers with DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] DNA Pol I has a 5′ to 3′ exonuclease activity in addition to its polymerase activity, and uses its exonuclease activity to degrade the RNA primers ahead of it as it extends the DNA strand behind it, in a process called nick translation.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Pol I is much less processive than Pol III because its primary function in DNA replication is to create many short DNA regions rather than a few very long regions.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In eukaryotes, the low-processivity enzyme, Pol α, helps to initiate replication because it forms a complex with primase.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In eukaryotes, leading strand synthesis is thought to be conducted by Pol ε; however, this view has recently been challenged, suggesting a role for Pol δ.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Primer removal is completed Pol δ while repair of DNA during replication is completed by Pol ε.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] As DNA synthesis continues, the original DNA strands continue to unwind on each side of the bubble, forming a replication fork with two prongs.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In bacteria, which have a single origin of replication on their circular chromosome, this process creates a "theta structure" (resembling the Greek letter theta: θ).
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In contrast, eukaryotes have longer linear chromosomes and initiate replication at multiple origins within these.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The replication fork is a structure that forms within the long helical DNA during DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] It is produced by enzymes called helicases that break the hydrogen bonds that hold the DNA strands together in a helix.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The resulting structure has two branching "prongs", each one made up of a single strand of DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] These two strands serve as the template for the leading and lagging strands, which will be created as DNA polymerase matches complementary nucleotides to the templates; the templates may be properly referred to as the leading strand template and the lagging strand template.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The leading strand is the strand of new DNA which is synthesized in the same direction as the growing replication fork.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] This sort of DNA replication is continuous.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The lagging strand is the strand of new DNA whose direction of synthesis is opposite to the direction of the growing replication fork, although the chemical reaction is exactly the same.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Because of its orientation, replication of the lagging strand is more complicated as compared to that of the leading strand.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] As a consequence, the DNA polymerase on this strand is seen to "lag behind" the other strand.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The lagging strand is synthesized in short segments.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] On the lagging strand *template*, a primase "reads" the template DNA and initiates synthesis of a short complementary RNA primer.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] A DNA polymerase extends the primed segments, forming Okazaki fragments.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The RNA primers are then removed by another DNA polymerase and replaced with DNA, and the fragments of DNA are joined by DNA ligase.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In all cases the helicase is composed of six polypeptides that wrap around only one strand of the DNA being replicated.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The two polymerases are bound to the helicase hexamer.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In eukaryotes the helicase wraps around the leading strand, and in prokaryotes it wraps around the lagging strand.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] As helicase unwinds DNA at the replication fork, the DNA ahead is forced to rotate.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] This process results in a build-up of twists in the DNA ahead.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] This build-up creates a torsional load that would eventually stop the replication fork.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Topoisomerases are enzymes that temporarily break the strands of DNA, relieving the tension caused by unwinding the two strands of the DNA helix; topoisomerases (including DNA gyrase) achieve this by adding negative supercoils to the DNA helix.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Bare single-stranded DNA tends to fold back on itself forming secondary structures; these structures can interfere with the movement of DNA polymerase.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] To prevent this, single-strand binding proteins bind to the DNA until a second strand is synthesized, preventing secondary structure formation.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Double-stranded DNA is coiled around histones that play an important role in regulating gene expression so the replicated DNA must be coiled around histones at the same places as the original DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] To ensure this, histone chaperones disassemble the chromatin before it is replicated and replace the histones in the correct place.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Some steps in this reassembly are somewhat speculative.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Clamp proteins act as a sliding clamp on DNA, allowing the DNA polymerase to bind to its template and aid in processivity.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The inner face of the clamp enables DNA to be threaded through it.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Once the polymerase reaches the end of the template or detects double-stranded DNA, the sliding clamp undergoes a conformational change that releases the DNA polymerase.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] At the replication fork, many replication enzymes assemble on the DNA into a complex molecular machine called the replisome.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In 1980 Bruce Alberts proposed the "trombone model" of DNA replication to visualize the coordination between the leading and lagging strand of DNA synthesis.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In this model the replication machinery is clustered while the leading strand synthesis flows through and the lagging strand expands in and out like the slide on a trombone.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Peter Meister et al. observed directly replication sites in budding yeast by monitoring green fluorescent protein (GFP)-tagged DNA polymerases α.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] They detected DNA replication of pairs of the tagged loci spaced apart symmetrically from a replication origin and found that the distance between the pairs decreased markedly by time.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] This finding suggests that the mechanism of DNA replication aligns with the trombone model with a cluster of replisomes loaded on the origin of replication, proceeding in both directions.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Meister's finding is the first direct evidence of trombone model.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Subsequent research has shown that DNA helicases form dimers in many eukaryotic cells and bacterial replisomes stay in a single intranuclear location during DNA synthesis.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Replication Factories Disentangle Sister Chromatids.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The disentanglement is essential for distributing the chromatids into daughter cells after DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Because sister chromatids after DNA replication hold each other by **cohesin** rings, there is the only chance for the disentanglement in DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Fixing of replication machineries as replication factories can improve the success rate of DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] If replication forks move freely in chromosomes, catenation of nuclei is aggravated and impedes mitotic segregation.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Eukaryotes initiate DNA replication at multiple points in the chromosome, so replication forks meet and terminate at many points in the chromosome.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Because eukaryotes have linear chromosomes, DNA replication is unable to reach the very end of the chromosomes.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Due to this problem, DNA is lost in each replication cycle from the end of the chromosome.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Telomeres are regions of repetitive DNA close to the ends and help prevent loss of genes due to this shortening.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Shortening of the telomeres is a normal process in somatic cells.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] This shortens the telomeres of the daughter DNA chromosome.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] As a result, cells can only divide a certain number of times before the DNA loss prevents further division.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] (This is known as the Hayflick limit.) Within the germ cell line, which passes DNA to the next generation, telomerase extends the repetitive sequences of the telomere region to prevent degradation.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Telomerase can become mistakenly active in somatic cells, sometimes leading to cancer formation.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Increased telomerase activity is one of the hallmarks of cancer.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Termination requires that the progress of the DNA replication fork must stop or be blocked.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Termination at a specific locus, when it occurs, involves the interaction between two components: (1) a termination site sequence in the DNA, and (2) a protein which binds to this sequence to physically stop DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In various bacterial species, this is named the DNA replication terminus site-binding protein, or Ter protein.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Because bacteria have circular chromosomes, termination of replication occurs when the two replication forks meet each other on the opposite end of the parental chromosome.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] *E. coli* regulates this process through the use of termination sequences that, when bound by the Tus protein, enable only one direction of replication fork to pass through.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] As a result, the replication forks are constrained to always meet within the termination region of the chromosome.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Within eukaryotes, DNA replication is controlled within the context of the cell cycle.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] As the cell grows and divides, it progresses through stages in the cell cycle; DNA replication takes place during the S phase (synthesis phase).
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The progress of the eukaryotic cell through the cycle is controlled by cell cycle checkpoints.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Progression through checkpoints is controlled through complex interactions between various proteins, including cyclins and cyclin-dependent kinases.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Unlike bacteria, eukaryotic DNA replicates in the confines of the nucleus.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The G1/S checkpoint (restriction checkpoint) regulates whether eukaryotic cells enter the process of DNA replication and subsequent division.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Cells that do not proceed through this checkpoint remain in the G0 stage and do not replicate their DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Once the DNA has gone through the "G1/S" test, it can only be copied once in every cell cycle.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] When the Mcm complex moves away from the origin, the pre-replication complex is dismantled.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Because a new Mcm complex cannot be loaded at an origin until the pre-replication subunits are reactivated, one origin of replication can not be used twice in the same cell cycle.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Activation of S-Cdks in early S phase promotes the destruction or inhibition of individual pre-replication complex components, preventing immediate reassembly.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] S and M-Cdks continue to block pre-replication complex assembly even after S phase is complete, ensuring that assembly cannot occur again until all Cdk activity is reduced in late mitosis.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In budding yeast, inhibition of assembly is caused by Cdk-dependent phosphorylation of pre-replication complex components.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] At the onset of S phase, phosphorylation of Cdc6 by Cdk1 causes the binding of Cdc6 to the SCF ubiquitin protein ligase, which causes proteolytic destruction of Cdc6.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Cdk-dependent phosphorylation of Mcm proteins promotes their export out of the nucleus along with Cdt1 during S phase, preventing the loading of new Mcm complexes at origins during a single cell cycle.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Cdk phosphorylation of the origin replication complex also inhibits pre-replication complex assembly.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The individual presence of any of these three mechanisms is sufficient to inhibit pre-replication complex assembly.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] However, mutations of all three proteins in the same cell does trigger reinitiation at many origins of replication within one cell cycle.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In animal cells, the protein geminin is a key inhibitor of pre-replication complex assembly.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Geminin binds Cdt1, preventing its binding to the origin recognition complex.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In G1, levels of geminin are kept low by the APC, which ubiquitinates geminin to target it for degradation.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] When geminin is destroyed, Cdt1 is released, allowing it to function in pre-replication complex assembly.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] At the end of G1, the APC is inactivated, allowing geminin to accumulate and bind Cdt1.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Replication of chloroplast and mitochondrial genomes occurs independently of the cell cycle, through the process of D-loop replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In vertebrate cells, replication sites concentrate into positions called **replication foci**.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Replication sites can be detected by immunostaining daughter strands and replication enzymes and monitoring GFP-tagged replication factors.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] By these methods it is found that replication foci of varying size and positions appear in S phase of cell division and their number per nucleus is far smaller than the number of genomic replication forks.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Heun *et al.* tracked GFP-tagged replication foci in budding yeast cells and revealed that replication origins move constantly in G1 and S phase and the dynamics decreased significantly in S phase.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Traditionally, replication sites were fixed on spatial structure of chromosomes by nuclear matrix or lamins.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The Heun's results denied the traditional concepts, budding yeasts do not have lamins, and support that replication origins self-assemble and form replication foci.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] By firing of replication origins, controlled spatially and temporally, the formation of replication foci is regulated.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Jackson et al.(1998) revealed that neighboring origins fire simultaneously in mammalian cells.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Spatial juxtaposition of replication sites brings **clustering** of replication forks.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The clustering do **rescue of stalled replication forks** and favors normal progress of replication forks.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Progress of replication forks is inhibited by many factors; collision with proteins or with complexes binding strongly on DNA, deficiency of dNTPs, nicks on template DNAs and so on.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] If replication forks get stuck and the rest of the sequences from the stuck forks are not copied, then the daughter strands get nick nick unreplicated sites.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The un-replicated sites on one parent's strand hold the other strand together but not daughter strands.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Therefore, the resulting sister chromatids cannot separate from each other and cannot divide into 2 daughter cells.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] When neighboring origins fire and a fork from one origin is stalled, fork from other origin access on an opposite direction of the stalled fork and duplicate the un-replicated sites.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] As other mechanism of the rescue there is application of **dormant replication origins** that excess origins do not fire in normal DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Most bacteria do not go through a well-defined cell cycle but instead continuously copy their DNA; during rapid growth, this can result in the concurrent occurrence of multiple rounds of replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In *E. coli*, the best-characterized bacteria, DNA replication is regulated through several mechanisms, including: the hemimethylation and sequestering of the origin sequence, the ratio of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to adenosine diphosphate (ADP), and the levels of protein DnaA.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] All these control the binding of initiator proteins to the origin sequences.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Because *E. coli* methylates GATC DNA sequences, DNA synthesis results in hemimethylated sequences.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] This hemimethylated DNA is recognized by the protein SeqA, which binds and sequesters the origin sequence; in addition, DnaA (required for initiation of replication) binds less well to hemimethylated DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] As a result, newly replicated origins are prevented from immediately initiating another round of DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] ATP builds up when the cell is in a rich medium, triggering DNA replication once the cell has reached a specific size.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] ATP competes with ADP to bind to DnaA, and the DnaA-ATP complex is able to initiate replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] A certain number of DnaA proteins are also required for DNA replication — each time the origin is copied, the number of binding sites for DnaA doubles, requiring the synthesis of more DnaA to enable another initiation of replication.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] In fast-growing bacteria, such as *E. coli*, chromosome replication takes more time than dividing the cell.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The bacteria solve this by initiating a new round of replication before the previous one has been terminated.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] The new round of replication will form the chromosome of the cell that is born two generations after the dividing cell.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] This mechanism creates overlapping replication cycles.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Researchers commonly replicate DNA *in vitro* using the polymerase chain reaction (PCR).
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] PCR uses a pair of primers to span a target region in template DNA, and then polymerizes partner strands in each direction from these primers using a thermostable DNA polymerase.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Repeating this process through multiple cycles amplifies the targeted DNA region.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] At the start of each cycle, the mixture of template and primers is heated, separating the newly synthesized molecule and template.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] Then, as the mixture cools, both of these become templates for annealing of new primers, and the polymerase extends from these.
[src:molecular-biology/dna-replication] As a result, the number of copies of the target region doubles each round, increasing exponentially.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The production of a RNA copy from a DNA strand is called transcription, and is performed by RNA polymerases, which add one ribonucleotide at a time to a growing RNA strand as per the complementarity law of the nucleotide bases.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] This RNA is complementary to the template 3′ → 5′ DNA strand, with the exception that thymines (T) are replaced with uracils (U) in the RNA and possible errors.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In bacteria, transcription is carried out by a single type of RNA polymerase, which needs to bind a DNA sequence called a Pribnow box with the help of the sigma factor protein (σ factor) to start transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In eukaryotes, transcription is performed in the nucleus by three types of RNA polymerases, each of which needs a special DNA sequence called the promoter and a set of DNA-binding proteins—transcription factors—to initiate the process (see regulation of transcription below).
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] RNA polymerase I is responsible for transcription of ribosomal RNA (rRNA) genes.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] RNA polymerase II (Pol II) transcribes all protein-coding genes but also some non-coding RNAs (*e.g.*, snRNAs, snoRNAs or long non-coding RNAs).
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] RNA polymerase III transcribes 5S rRNA, transfer RNA (tRNA) genes, and some small non-coding RNAs (*e.g.*, 7SK).
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Transcription ends when the polymerase encounters a sequence called the terminator.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] While transcription of prokaryotic protein-coding genes creates messenger RNA (mRNA) that is ready for translation into protein, transcription of eukaryotic genes leaves a primary transcript of RNA (pre-RNA), which first has to undergo a series of modifications to become a mature RNA.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Types and steps involved in the maturation processes vary between coding and non-coding preRNAs; *i.e.* even though preRNA molecules for both mRNA and tRNA undergo splicing, the steps and machinery involved are different.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The processing of non-coding RNA is described below (non-coding RNA maturation).
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The processing of pre-mRNA include 5′ *capping*, which is set of enzymatic reactions that add 7-methylguanosine (m7G) to the 5′ end of pre-mRNA and thus protect the RNA from degradation by exonucleases.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The m7G cap is then bound by cap binding complex heterodimer (CBP20/CBP80), which aids in mRNA export to cytoplasm and also protect the RNA from decapping.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Another modification is 3′ *cleavage and polyadenylation*.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] They occur if polyadenylation signal sequence (5′- AAUAAA-3′) is present in pre-mRNA, which is usually between protein-coding sequence and terminator.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The pre-mRNA is first cleaved and then a series of ~200 adenines (A) are added to form poly(A) tail, which protects the RNA from degradation.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The poly(A) tail is bound by multiple poly(A)-binding proteins (PABPs) necessary for mRNA export and translation re-initiation.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In the inverse process of deadenylation, poly(A) tails are shortened by the CCR4-Not 3′-5′ exonuclease, which often leads to full transcript decay.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] A very important modification of eukaryotic pre-mRNA is *RNA splicing*.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The majority of eukaryotic pre-mRNAs consist of alternating segments called exons and introns.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] During the process of splicing, an RNA-protein catalytical complex known as spliceosome catalyzes two transesterification reactions, which remove an intron and release it in form of lariat structure, and then splice neighbouring exons together.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In certain cases, some introns or exons can be either removed or retained in mature mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] This so-called alternative splicing creates series of different transcripts originating from a single gene.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Because these transcripts can be potentially translated into different proteins, splicing extends the complexity of eukaryotic gene expression and the size of a species proteome.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Extensive RNA processing may be an evolutionary advantage made possible by the nucleus of eukaryotes.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In prokaryotes, transcription and translation happen together, whilst in eukaryotes, the nuclear membrane separates the two processes, giving time for RNA processing to occur.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In most organisms non-coding genes (ncRNA) are transcribed as precursors that undergo further processing.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In the case of ribosomal RNAs (rRNA), they are often transcribed as a pre-rRNA that contains one or more rRNAs.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The pre-rRNA is cleaved and modified (2′-*O*-methylation and pseudouridine formation) at specific sites by approximately 150 different small nucleolus-restricted RNA species, called snoRNAs.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] SnoRNAs associate with proteins, forming snoRNPs.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] While snoRNA part basepair with the target RNA and thus position the modification at a precise site, the protein part performs the catalytical reaction.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In eukaryotes, in particular a snoRNP called RNase, MRP cleaves the 45S pre-rRNA into the 28S, 5.8S, and 18S rRNAs.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The rRNA and RNA processing factors form large aggregates called the nucleolus.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In the case of transfer RNA (tRNA), for example, the 5′ sequence is removed by RNase P, whereas the 3′ end is removed by the tRNase Z enzyme and the non-templated 3′ CCA tail is added by a nucleotidyl transferase.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In the case of micro RNA (miRNA), miRNAs are first transcribed as primary transcripts or pri-miRNA with a cap and poly-A tail and processed to short, 70-nucleotide stem-loop structures known as pre-miRNA in the cell nucleus by the enzymes Drosha and Pasha.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] After being exported, it is then processed to mature miRNAs in the cytoplasm by interaction with the endonuclease Dicer, which also initiates the formation of the RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC), composed of the Argonaute protein.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Even snRNAs and snoRNAs themselves undergo series of modification before they become part of functional RNP complex.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] This is done either in the nucleoplasm or in the specialized compartments called Cajal bodies.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Their bases are methylated or pseudouridinilated by a group of small Cajal body-specific RNAs (scaRNAs), which are structurally similar to snoRNAs.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] For some non-coding RNA, the mature RNA is the final gene product.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In the case of messenger RNA (mRNA) the RNA is an information carrier coding for the synthesis of one or more proteins. mRNA carrying a single protein sequence (common in eukaryotes) is monocistronic whilst mRNA carrying multiple protein sequences (common in prokaryotes) is known as polycistronic.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Every mRNA consists of three parts: a 5′ untranslated region (5′UTR), a protein-coding region or open reading frame (ORF), and a 3′ untranslated region (3′UTR).
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The coding region carries information for protein synthesis encoded by the genetic code to form triplets.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Each triplet of nucleotides of the coding region is called a codon and corresponds to a binding site complementary to an anticodon triplet in transfer RNA.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Transfer RNAs with the same anticodon sequence always carry an identical type of amino acid.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Amino acids are then chained together by the ribosome according to the order of triplets in the coding region.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The ribosome helps transfer RNA to bind to messenger RNA and takes the amino acid from each transfer RNA and makes a structure-less protein out of it.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Each mRNA molecule is translated into many protein molecules, on average ~2800 in mammals.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In prokaryotes translation generally occurs at the point of transcription (co-transcriptionally), often using a messenger RNA that is still in the process of being created.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In eukaryotes translation can occur in a variety of regions of the cell depending on where the protein being written is supposed to be.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Major locations are the cytoplasm for soluble cytoplasmic proteins and the membrane of the endoplasmic reticulum for proteins that are for export from the cell or insertion into a cell membrane.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Proteins that are supposed to be produced at the endoplasmic reticulum are recognised part-way through the translation process.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] This is governed by the signal recognition particle—a protein that binds to the ribosome and directs it to the endoplasmic reticulum when it finds a signal peptide on the growing (nascent) amino acid chain.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Regulation of gene expression is the control of the amount and timing of appearance of the functional product of a gene.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Control of expression is vital to allow a cell to produce the gene products it needs when it needs them; in turn, this gives cells the flexibility to adapt to a variable environment, external signals, damage to the cell, and other stimuli.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] More generally, gene regulation gives the cell control over all structure and function, and is the basis for cellular differentiation, morphogenesis and the versatility and adaptability of any organism.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Any step of gene expression may be modulated, from the DNA-RNA transcription step to post-translational modification of a protein.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The stability of the final gene product, whether it is RNA or protein, also contributes to the expression level of the gene—an unstable product results in a low expression level.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In general gene expression is regulated through changes in the number and type of interactions between molecules that collectively influence transcription of DNA and translation of RNA.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Direct interaction with DNA is the simplest and the most direct method by which a protein changes transcription levels.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Genes often have several protein binding sites around the coding region with the specific function of regulating transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] There are many classes of regulatory DNA binding sites known as enhancers, insulators and silencers.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The mechanisms for regulating transcription are varied, from blocking key binding sites on the DNA for RNA polymerase to acting as an activator and promoting transcription by assisting RNA polymerase binding.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The activity of transcription factors is further modulated by intracellular signals causing protein post-translational modification including phosphorylation, acetylation, or glycosylation.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] These changes influence a transcription factor's ability to bind, directly or indirectly, to promoter DNA, to recruit RNA polymerase, or to favor elongation of a newly synthesized RNA molecule.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The nuclear membrane in eukaryotes allows further regulation of transcription factors by the duration of their presence in the nucleus, which is regulated by reversible changes in their structure and by binding of other proteins.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Environmental stimuli or endocrine signals may cause modification of regulatory proteins eliciting cascades of intracellular signals, which result in regulation of gene expression.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] It has become apparent that there is a significant influence of non-DNA-sequence specific effects on transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] These effects are referred to as epigenetic and involve the higher order structure of DNA, non-sequence specific DNA binding proteins and chemical modification of DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In general epigenetic effects alter the accessibility of DNA to proteins and so modulate transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In eukaryotes the structure of chromatin, controlled by the histone code, regulates access to DNA with significant impacts on the expression of genes in euchromatin and heterochromatin areas.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Gene expression in mammals is regulated by many cis-regulatory elements, including core promoters and promoter-proximal elements that are located near the transcription start sites of genes, upstream on the DNA (towards the 5' region of the sense strand).
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Other important cis-regulatory modules are localized in DNA regions that are distant from the transcription start sites.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] These include enhancers, silencers, insulators and tethering elements.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Enhancers and their associated transcription factors have a leading role in the regulation of gene expression.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Enhancers are genome regions that regulate genes.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Enhancers control cell-type-specific gene expression programs, most often by looping through long distances to come in physical proximity with the promoters of their target genes.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Multiple enhancers, each often tens or hundred of thousands of nucleotides distant from their target genes, loop to their target gene promoters and coordinate with each other to control gene expression.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The illustration shows an enhancer looping around to come into proximity with the promoter of a target gene.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The loop is stabilized by a dimer of a connector protein (e.g. dimer of CTCF or YY1).
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] One member of the dimer is anchored to its binding motif on the enhancer and the other member is anchored to its binding motif on the promoter (represented by the red zigzags in the illustration).
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Several cell function-specific transcription factors (among the about 1,600 transcription factors in a human cell) generally bind to specific motifs on an enhancer.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] A small combination of these enhancer-bound transcription factors, when brought close to a promoter by a DNA loop, govern transcription level of the target gene.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Mediator (a complex usually consisting of about 26 proteins in an interacting structure) communicates regulatory signals from enhancer DNA-bound transcription factors directly to the RNA polymerase II (pol II) enzyme bound to the promoter.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Enhancers, when active, are generally transcribed from both strands of DNA with RNA polymerases acting in two different directions, producing two eRNAs as illustrated in the figure.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] An inactive enhancer may be bound by an inactive transcription factor.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Phosphorylation of the transcription factor may activate it and that activated transcription factor may then activate the enhancer to which it is bound (see small red star representing phosphorylation of transcription factor bound to enhancer in the illustration).
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] An activated enhancer begins transcription of its RNA before activating transcription of messenger RNA from its target gene.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] DNA methylation is a widespread mechanism for epigenetic influence on gene expression and is seen in bacteria and eukaryotes and has roles in heritable transcription silencing and transcription regulation.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Methylation most often occurs on a cytosine (see Figure).
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Methylation of cytosine primarily occurs in dinucleotide sequences where a cytosine is followed by a guanine, a CpG site.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The number of CpG sites in the human genome is about 28 million.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Depending on the type of cell, about 70% of the CpG sites have a methylated cytosine.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Methylation of cytosine in DNA has a major role in regulating gene expression.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Methylation of CpGs in a promoter region of a gene usually represses gene transcription while methylation of CpGs in the body of a gene increases expression.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] TET enzymes play a central role in demethylation of methylated cytosines.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Demethylation of CpGs in a gene promoter by TET enzyme activity increases transcription of the gene.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In eukaryotes, where export of RNA is required before translation is possible, nuclear export is thought to provide additional control over gene expression.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] All transport in and out of the nucleus is via the nuclear pore and transport is controlled by a wide range of importin and exportin proteins.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Expression of a gene coding for a protein is only possible if the messenger RNA carrying the code survives long enough to be translated.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In a typical cell, an RNA molecule is only stable if specifically protected from degradation.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] RNA degradation has particular importance in regulation of expression in eukaryotic cells where mRNA has to travel significant distances before being translated.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In eukaryotes, RNA is stabilised by certain post-transcriptional modifications, particularly the 5′ cap and poly-adenylated tail.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Intentional degradation of mRNA is used not just as a defence mechanism from foreign RNA (normally from viruses) but also as a route of mRNA *destabilisation*.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] If an mRNA molecule has a complementary sequence to a small interfering RNA then it is targeted for destruction via the RNA interference pathway.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Three prime untranslated regions (3′UTRs) of messenger RNAs (mRNAs) often contain regulatory sequences that post-transcriptionally influence gene expression.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Such 3′-UTRs often contain both binding sites for microRNAs (miRNAs) as well as for regulatory proteins.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] By binding to specific sites within the 3′-UTR, miRNAs can decrease gene expression of various mRNAs by either inhibiting translation or directly causing degradation of the transcript.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The 3′-UTR also may have silencer regions that bind repressor proteins that inhibit the expression of a mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The 3′-UTR often contains microRNA response elements (MREs).
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] MREs are sequences to which miRNAs bind.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] These are prevalent motifs within 3′-UTRs.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Among all regulatory motifs within the 3′-UTRs (e.g. including silencer regions), MREs make up about half of the motifs.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] As of 2014, the miRBase web site, an archive of miRNA sequences and annotations, listed 28,645 entries in 233 biologic species.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Of these, 1,881 miRNAs were in annotated human miRNA loci. miRNAs were predicted to have an average of about four hundred target mRNAs (affecting expression of several hundred genes).
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Friedman et al. estimate that >45,000 miRNA target sites within human mRNA 3′UTRs are conserved above background levels, and >60% of human protein-coding genes have been under selective pressure to maintain pairing to miRNAs.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Direct experiments show that a single miRNA can reduce the stability of hundreds of unique mRNAs.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Other experiments show that a single miRNA may repress the production of hundreds of proteins, but that this repression often is relatively mild (less than 2-fold).
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The effects of miRNA dysregulation of gene expression seem to be important in cancer.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] For instance, in gastrointestinal cancers, nine miRNAs have been identified as epigenetically altered and effective in down regulating DNA repair enzymes.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The effects of miRNA dysregulation of gene expression also seem to be important in neuropsychiatric disorders, such as schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, major depression, Parkinson's disease, Alzheimer's disease and autism spectrum disorders.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Direct regulation of translation is less prevalent than control of transcription or mRNA stability but is occasionally used.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Inhibition of protein translation is a major target for toxins and antibiotics, so they can kill a cell by overriding its normal gene expression control.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Protein synthesis inhibitors include the antibiotic neomycin and the toxin ricin.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Post-translational modifications (PTMs) are covalent modifications to proteins.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Like RNA splicing, they help to significantly diversify the proteome.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] These modifications are usually catalyzed by enzymes.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Additionally, processes like covalent additions to amino acid side chain residues can often be reversed by other enzymes.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] However, some, like the proteolytic cleavage of the protein backbone, are irreversible.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] PTMs play many important roles in the cell.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] For example, phosphorylation is primarily involved in activating and deactivating proteins and in signaling pathways.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] PTMs are involved in transcriptional regulation: an important function of acetylation and methylation is histone tail modification, which alters how accessible DNA is for transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] They can also be seen in the immune system, where glycosylation plays a key role.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] One type of PTM can initiate another type of PTM, as can be seen in how ubiquitination tags proteins for degradation through proteolysis.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Proteolysis, other than being involved in breaking down proteins, is also important in activating and deactivating them, and in regulating biological processes such as DNA transcription and cell death.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Measuring gene expression is an important part of many life sciences, as the ability to quantify the level at which a particular gene is expressed within a cell, tissue or organism can provide a lot of valuable information.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Similarly, the analysis of the location of protein expression is a powerful tool, and this can be done on an organismal or cellular scale.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Investigation of localization is particularly important for the study of development in multicellular organisms and as an indicator of protein function in single cells.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Ideally, measurement of expression is done by detecting the final gene product (for many genes, this is the protein); however, it is often easier to detect one of the precursors, typically mRNA and to infer gene-expression levels from these measurements.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Levels of mRNA can be quantitatively measured by northern blotting, which provides size and sequence information about the mRNA molecules.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] A sample of RNA is separated on an agarose gel and hybridized to a radioactively labeled RNA probe that is complementary to the target sequence.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The radiolabeled RNA is then detected by an autoradiograph.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Because the use of radioactive reagents makes the procedure time-consuming and potentially dangerous, alternative labeling and detection methods, such as digoxigenin and biotin chemistries, have been developed.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Perceived disadvantages of Northern blotting are that large quantities of RNA are required and that quantification may not be completely accurate, as it involves measuring band strength in an image of a gel.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] On the other hand, the additional mRNA size information from the Northern blot allows the discrimination of alternately spliced transcripts.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Another approach for measuring mRNA abundance is RT-qPCR.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] In this technique, reverse transcription is followed by quantitative PCR.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Reverse transcription first generates a DNA template from the mRNA; this single-stranded template is called cDNA.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The cDNA template is then amplified in the quantitative step, during which the fluorescence emitted by labeled hybridization probes or intercalating dyes changes as the DNA amplification process progresses.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] For expression profiling, or high-throughput analysis of many genes within a sample, quantitative PCR may be performed for hundreds of genes simultaneously in the case of low-density arrays.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] A second approach is the hybridization microarray.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] A single array or "chip" may contain probes to determine transcript levels for every known gene in the genome of one or more organisms.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Alternatively, "tag based" technologies like Serial analysis of gene expression (SAGE) and RNA-Seq, which can provide a relative measure of the cellular concentration of different mRNAs, can be used.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] An advantage of tag-based methods is the "open architecture", allowing for the exact measurement of any transcript, with a known or unknown sequence.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Next-generation sequencing (NGS) such as RNA-Seq is another approach, producing vast quantities of sequence data that can be matched to a reference genome.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Although NGS is comparatively time-consuming, expensive, and resource-intensive, it can identify single-nucleotide polymorphisms, splice-variants, and novel genes, and can also be used to profile expression in organisms for which little or no sequence information is available.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] For genes encoding proteins, the expression level can be directly assessed by a number of methods with some clear analogies to the techniques for mRNA quantification.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] One of the most commonly used methods is to perform a Western blot against the protein of interest.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] This gives information on the size of the protein in addition to its identity.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] A sample (often cellular lysate) is separated on a polyacrylamide gel, transferred to a membrane and then probed with an antibody to the protein of interest.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The antibody can either be conjugated to a fluorophore or to horseradish peroxidase for imaging and/or quantification.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The gel-based nature of this assay makes quantification less accurate, but it has the advantage of being able to identify later modifications to the protein, for example proteolysis or ubiquitination, from changes in size.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] While transcription directly reflects gene expression, the copy number of mRNA molecules does not directly correlate with the number of protein molecules translated from mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Quantification of both protein and mRNA permits a correlation of the two levels.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Regulation on each step of gene expression can impact the correlation, as shown for regulation of translation or protein stability.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Post-translational factors, such as protein transport in highly polar cells, can influence the measured mRNA-protein correlation as well.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Analysis of expression is not limited to quantification; localization can also be determined. mRNA can be detected with a suitably labelled complementary mRNA strand and protein can be detected via labelled antibodies.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The probed sample is then observed by microscopy to identify where the mRNA or protein is.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] By replacing the gene with a new version fused to a green fluorescent protein marker or similar, expression may be directly quantified in live cells.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] This is done by imaging using a fluorescence microscope.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] It is very difficult to clone a GFP-fused protein into its native location in the genome without affecting expression levels, so this method often cannot be used to measure endogenous gene expression.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] It is, however, widely used to measure the expression of a gene artificially introduced into the cell, for example via an expression vector.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] By fusing a target protein to a fluorescent reporter, the protein's behavior, including its cellular localization and expression level, can be significantly changed.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay works by using antibodies immobilised on a microtiter plate to capture proteins of interest from samples added to the well.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] Using a detection antibody conjugated to an enzyme or fluorophore the quantity of bound protein can be accurately measured by fluorometric or colourimetric detection.
[src:molecular-biology/gene-expression] The detection process is very similar to that of a Western blot, but by avoiding the gel steps more accurate quantification can be achieved.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] mRNA is created during the process of transcription, where an enzyme (RNA polymerase) converts the gene into primary transcript mRNA (also known as pre-mRNA).
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] This pre-mRNA usually still contains introns, regions that will not go on to code for the final amino acid sequence.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] These are removed in the process of RNA splicing, leaving only exons, regions that will encode the protein.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] This exon sequence constitutes mature mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Mature mRNA is then read by the ribosome, and the ribosome creates the protein utilizing amino acids carried by transfer RNA (tRNA).
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] All of these processes form part of the central dogma of molecular biology, which describes the flow of genetic information in a biological system.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] As in DNA, genetic information in mRNA is contained in the sequence of nucleotides, which are arranged into codons consisting of three ribonucleotides each.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Each codon codes for a specific amino acid, except the stop codons, which terminate protein synthesis.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The translation of codons into amino acids requires two other types of RNA: transfer RNA, which recognizes the codon and provides the corresponding amino acid, and ribosomal RNA (rRNA), the central component of the ribosome's protein-manufacturing machinery.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The concept of mRNA was first conceived by Sydney Brenner and Francis Crick in 1960 during a conversation with François Jacob.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In May 1961, messenger RNA was experimentally characterized in two back-to-back *Nature* papers: one by Brenner, Jacob, and Meselson, and one by Gros and colleagues (including Watson).
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] While analyzing the data in preparation for publication, Jacob and Jacques Monod coined the term "messenger RNA".
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The brief existence of an mRNA molecule begins with transcription, and ultimately ends in degradation.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] During its life, an mRNA molecule may also be processed, edited, and transported prior to translation.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Eukaryotic mRNA molecules often require extensive processing and transport, while prokaryotic mRNA molecules do not.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] A molecule of eukaryotic mRNA and the proteins surrounding it are together called a messenger RNP.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Transcription is the process by which genetic information stored in DNA is copied into RNA by the enzyme RNA polymerase.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] During transcription, RNA polymerase binds to a promoter sequence on the DNA and synthesizes a complementary RNA strand (mRNA) from the DNA template.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] This process differs between prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In prokaryotes, transcription occurs in the cytoplasm.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Because prokaryotes lack a membrane-bound nucleus, ribosomes can attach to the nascent mRNA strand and begin translation while transcription is still in progress.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In eukaryotes, transcription occurs within the cell nucleus.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The initial product of transcription is not functional mRNA but is termed *precursor mRNA* or *pre-mRNA*.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] This pre-mRNA must undergo extensive processing (including 5' capping, splicing to remove non-coding introns, and 3' polyadenylation) to become *mature mRNA*.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Once processed, the mature mRNA is exported from the nucleus to the cytoplasm for translation.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Whereas DNA contains thymine (T), RNA contains uracil (U).
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] During the process of transcription, the enzyme RNA polymerase incorporates uracil opposite adenine bases located on the DNA template strand.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Therefore, the resulting RNA transcript contains uracil in the positions where the coding DNA strand contains thymine.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Structurally, uracil–adenine (U–A) base pairs closely resemble thymine–adenine (T–A) base pairs, which ensures that the genetic information carried by the sequence is faithfully preserved.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] A frequently cited explanation for the presence of thymine in DNA involves the necessity of genome maintenance.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Because cytosine can spontaneously deaminate to form uracil, DNA repair systems recognize uracil as a form of damage.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The utilization of thymine as a standard base allows the cell to distinguish legitimate bases from errors, thereby maintaining uracil as a specific signal for repair.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Processing of mRNA differs greatly among eukaryotes, bacteria, and archaea.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Non-eukaryotic mRNA is, in essence, mature upon transcription and requires no processing, except in rare cases.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Eukaryotic pre-mRNA, however, requires several processing steps before its transport to the cytoplasm and its translation by the ribosome.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The extensive processing of eukaryotic pre-mRNA that leads to the mature mRNA is the RNA splicing, a mechanism by which introns or outrons (non-coding regions) are removed and exons (coding regions) are joined.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] A *5' cap* (also termed an RNA cap, an RNA 7-methylguanosine cap, or an RNA m7G cap) is a modified guanine nucleotide that has been added to the "front" or 5' end of a eukaryotic messenger RNA shortly after the start of transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The 5' cap consists of a terminal 7-methylguanosine residue that is linked through a 5'-5'-triphosphate bond to the first transcribed nucleotide.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Its presence is critical for recognition by the ribosome and protection from RNases.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Cap addition is coupled to transcription, and occurs co-transcriptionally, such that each influences the other.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Shortly after the start of transcription, the 5' end of the mRNA being synthesized is bound by a cap-synthesizing complex associated with RNA polymerase.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] This enzymatic complex catalyzes the chemical reactions that are required for mRNA capping.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Synthesis proceeds as a multi-step biochemical reaction.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In some instances, an mRNA molecule is edited, which changes the nucleotide composition of the transcript.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] A prominent example in humans involves the apolipoprotein B mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In certain tissues, RNA editing of this transcript creates a premature stop codon, which results in the production of a shorter protein variant.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Another well studied mechanism is A-to-I (adenosine-to-inosine) editing.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] This reaction is catalyzed by ADAR enzymes (adenosine deaminase acting on RNA) and typically occurs within double-stranded RNA regions.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] A-to-I editing may occur in both coding sequences and untranslated regions.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Through these modifications, the process can affect protein recoding, RNA structure, and gene regulation.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Polyadenylation is the covalent linkage of a polyadenylyl moiety to a messenger RNA molecule.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In eukaryotic organisms most messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules are polyadenylated at the 3' end, but recent studies have shown that short stretches of uridine (oligouridylation) are also common.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The poly(A) tail and the protein bound to it aid in protecting mRNA from degradation by exonucleases.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Polyadenylation is also important for transcription termination, export of the mRNA from the nucleus, and translation. mRNA can also be polyadenylated in prokaryotic organisms, where poly(A) tails act to facilitate, rather than impede, exonucleolytic degradation.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Polyadenylation occurs during and/or immediately after transcription of DNA into RNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] After transcription has been terminated, the mRNA chain is cleaved through the action of an endonuclease complex associated with RNA polymerase.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] After the mRNA has been cleaved, around 200–250 adenosine residues are added to the free 3' end at the cleavage site.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] This reaction is catalyzed by polyadenylate polymerase.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Just as in alternative splicing, there can be more than one polyadenylation variant of an mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Polyadenylation site mutations can occur.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The primary RNA transcript of a gene is cleaved at the poly(A) addition site, and about 150–250 adenosines are added to the 3′ end of the RNA as a poly(A) tail.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] If this site is altered, cleavage and polyadenylation can shift to a downstream poly(A) site, producing an abnormally long and unstable mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Another difference between eukaryotes and prokaryotes is mRNA transport.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Because eukaryotic transcription and translation is compartmentally separated, eukaryotic mRNAs must be exported from the nucleus to the cytoplasm—a process that may be regulated by different signaling pathways.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Mature mRNAs are recognized by their processed modifications and then exported through the nuclear pore by binding to the cap-binding proteins CBP20 and CBP80, as well as the transcription/export complex (TREX).
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Multiple mRNA export pathways have been identified in eukaryotes.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In spatially complex cells, some mRNAs are transported to particular subcellular destinations.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In mature neurons, certain mRNA are transported from the soma to dendrites.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] One site of mRNA translation is at polyribosomes selectively localized beneath synapses.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The mRNA for Arc/Arg3.1 is induced by synaptic activity and localizes selectively near active synapses based on signals generated by NMDA receptors.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Other mRNAs also move into dendrites in response to external stimuli, such as β-actin mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] For export from the nucleus, actin mRNA associates with ZBP1 and later with 40S subunit.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The complex is bound by a motor protein and is transported to the target location (neurite extension) along the cytoskeleton.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Eventually ZBP1 is phosphorylated by Src in order for translation to be initiated.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In developing neurons, mRNAs are also transported into growing axons and especially growth cones.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Many mRNAs are marked with so-called "zip codes", which target their transport to a specific location. mRNAs can also transfer between mammalian cells through structures called tunneling nanotubes.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Because prokaryotic mRNA does not need to be processed or transported, translation by the ribosome can begin immediately after the end of transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Therefore, it can be said that prokaryotic translation is *coupled* to transcription and occurs *co-transcriptionally*.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In eukaryotic cells the process of translation starts with the information stored in the nucleotide sequence of DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] This is first transformed into mRNA, then transfer RNA (tRNA) specifies which three-nucleotide codon from the genetic code corresponds to which amino acid.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Eukaryotic mRNA that has been processed and transported to the cytoplasm (i.e., mature mRNA) can then be translated by ribosomes.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Translation may occur at ribosomes free in the cytoplasm, or targeted to the endoplasmic reticulum by the signal recognition particle.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Therefore, unlike in prokaryotes, eukaryotic translation is not directly coupled to transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In some contexts, protein abundance can increase even when mRNA abundance decreases, because translation efficiency and protein turnover are regulated independently of transcript levels; this has been reported for mRNA and protein levels of EEF1A1 in breast cancer.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Coding regions are composed of codons, which are decoded and translated into proteins by the ribosome; in eukaryotes usually into one and in prokaryotes usually into several.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Coding regions begin with the start codon and end with a stop codon.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In general, the start codon is an AUG triplet and the stop codon is UAG ("amber"), UAA ("ochre"), or UGA ("opal").
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The coding regions tend to be stabilized by internal base pairs; this impedes degradation.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In addition to being protein-coding, portions of coding regions may serve as regulatory sequences in the pre-mRNA as exonic splicing enhancers or exonic splicing silencers.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Untranslated regions (UTRs) are sections of the mRNA before the start codon and after the stop codon that are not translated, termed the five prime untranslated region (5' UTR) and three prime untranslated region (3' UTR), respectively.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] These regions are transcribed with the coding region and thus are exonic as they are present in the mature mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Several roles in gene expression have been attributed to the untranslated regions, including mRNA stability, mRNA localization, and translational efficiency.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The ability of a UTR to perform these functions depends on the sequence of the UTR and can differ between mRNAs.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Genetic variants in 3' UTR have also been implicated in disease susceptibility because of the change in RNA structure and protein translation.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The stability of mRNAs may be controlled by the 5' UTR and/or 3' UTR due to varying affinity for RNA degrading enzymes called ribonucleases and for ancillary proteins that can promote or inhibit RNA degradation.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Translational efficiency, including sometimes the complete inhibition of translation, can be controlled by UTRs.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Proteins that bind to either the 3' or 5' UTR may affect translation by influencing the ribosome's ability to bind to the mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] MicroRNAs bound to the 3' UTR also may affect translational efficiency or mRNA stability.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Cytoplasmic localization of mRNA is thought to be a function of the 3' UTR.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Proteins that are needed in a particular region of the cell can also be translated there; in such a case, the 3' UTR may contain sequences that allow the transcript to be localized to this region for translation.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Some of the elements contained in untranslated regions form a characteristic secondary structure when transcribed into RNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] These structural mRNA elements are involved in regulating the mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Some, such as the SECIS element, are targets for proteins to bind.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] One class of mRNA element, the riboswitches, directly bind small molecules, changing their fold to modify levels of transcription or translation.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In these cases, the mRNA regulates itself.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The 3' poly(A) tail is a long sequence of adenine nucleotides (often several hundred) added to the 3' end of the pre-mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] This tail promotes export from the nucleus and translation, and protects the mRNA from degradation.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] An mRNA molecule is said to be monocistronic when it contains the genetic information to translate only a single protein chain (polypeptide).
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] This is the case for most of the eukaryotic mRNAs.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] On the other hand, polycistronic mRNA carries several open reading frames (ORFs), each of which is translated into a polypeptide.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] These polypeptides usually have a related function (they often are the subunits composing a final complex protein) and their coding sequence is grouped and regulated together in a regulatory region, containing a promoter and an operator.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Most of the mRNA found in bacteria and archaea is polycistronic, as is the human mitochondrial genome.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Dicistronic or bicistronic mRNA encodes only two proteins.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In eukaryotes mRNA molecules form circular structures due to an interaction between the eIF4E and poly(A)-binding protein, which both bind to eIF4G, forming an mRNA-protein-mRNA bridge.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Circularization is thought to promote cycling of ribosomes on the mRNA leading to time-efficient translation, and may also function to ensure only intact mRNA are translated (partially degraded mRNA characteristically have no m7G cap, or no poly-A tail).
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Other mechanisms for circularization exist, particularly in viruses.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In several RNA viruses, long-distance RNA interactions and/or protein-mediated bridges between the 5' and 3' ends can promote translation and genome replication.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] RNA virus genomes (the + strands of which are translated as mRNA) are also commonly circularized.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Different mRNAs within the same cell have distinct lifetimes (stabilities).
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In bacterial cells, individual mRNAs can survive from seconds to more than an hour.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] However, the lifetime averages between 1 and 3 minutes, making bacterial mRNA much less stable than eukaryotic mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In mammalian cells, mRNA lifetimes range from several minutes to days.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The greater the stability of an mRNA the more protein may be produced from that mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The limited lifetime of mRNA enables a cell to alter protein synthesis rapidly in response to its changing needs.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] There are many mechanisms that lead to the destruction of an mRNA, some of which are described below.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In general, in prokaryotes the lifetime of mRNA is much shorter than in eukaryotes.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Prokaryotes degrade messages by using a combination of ribonucleases, including endonucleases, 3' exonucleases, and 5' exonucleases.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In some instances, small RNA molecules (sRNA) tens to hundreds of nucleotides long can stimulate the degradation of specific mRNAs by base-pairing with complementary sequences and facilitating ribonuclease cleavage by RNase III.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] It was recently shown that bacteria also have a sort of 5' cap consisting of a triphosphate on the 5' end.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Removal of two of the phosphates leaves a 5' monophosphate, causing the message to be destroyed by the exonuclease RNase J, which degrades 5' to 3'.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Inside eukaryotic cells, there is a balance between the processes of translation and mRNA decay.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Messages that are being actively translated are typically associated with cap-binding and translation initiation factors and with poly(A)-binding protein, which can antagonize deadenylation and decapping and help protect mRNA ends from decay machinery.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The balance between translation and decay is reflected in the size and abundance of cytoplasmic structures known as P-bodies.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The poly(A) tail of the mRNA is shortened by specialized exonucleases that are targeted to specific messenger RNAs by a combination of cis-regulatory sequences on the RNA and trans-acting RNA-binding proteins.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Poly(A) tail removal is thought to disrupt the circular structure of the message and destabilize the cap binding complex.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The message is then subject to degradation by either the exosome complex or the decapping complex.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In this way, translationally inactive messages can be destroyed quickly, while active messages remain intact.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The mechanism by which translation stops and the message is handed-off to decay complexes is not understood in detail.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The majority of mRNA decay was believed to be cytoplasmic; however, recently, a novel mRNA decay pathway was described, which starts in the nucleus.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The presence of AU-rich elements in some mammalian mRNAs tends to destabilize those transcripts through the action of cellular proteins that bind these sequences and stimulate poly(A) tail removal.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Loss of the poly(A) tail is thought to promote mRNA degradation by facilitating attack by both the exosome complex and the decapping complex.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Rapid mRNA degradation via AU-rich elements is a critical mechanism for preventing the overproduction of potent cytokines such as tumor necrosis factor (TNF) and granulocyte-macrophage colony stimulating factor (GM-CSF).
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] AU-rich elements also regulate the biosynthesis of proto-oncogenic transcription factors like c-Jun and c-Fos.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Eukaryotic messages are subject to surveillance by nonsense-mediated decay (NMD), which checks for the presence of premature stop codons (nonsense codons) in the message.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] These can arise via incomplete splicing, V(D)J recombination in the adaptive immune system, mutations in DNA, transcription errors, leaky scanning by the ribosome causing a frame shift, and other causes.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Detection of a premature stop codon triggers mRNA degradation by 5' decapping, 3' poly(A) tail removal, or endonucleolytic cleavage.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In metazoans, small interfering RNAs (siRNAs) processed by Dicer are incorporated into a complex known as the RNA-induced silencing complex or RISC.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] This complex contains an endonuclease that cleaves perfectly complementary messages to which the siRNA binds.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The resulting mRNA fragments are then destroyed by exonucleases. siRNA is commonly used in laboratories to block the function of genes in cell culture.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] It is thought to be part of the innate immune system as a defense against double-stranded RNA viruses.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] MicroRNAs (miRNAs) are small RNAs that typically are partially complementary to sequences in metazoan messenger RNAs.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Binding of a miRNA to a message can repress translation of that message and accelerate poly(A) tail removal, thereby hastening mRNA degradation.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The mechanism of action of miRNAs is the subject of active research.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] There are other ways by which messages can be degraded, including non-stop decay and silencing by Piwi-interacting RNA (piRNA), among others.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The administration of a nucleoside-modified messenger RNA sequence can cause a cell to make a protein, which in turn could directly treat a disease or could function as a vaccine; more indirectly the protein could drive an endogenous stem cell to differentiate in a desired way.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The primary challenges of RNA therapy center on delivering the RNA to the appropriate cells.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Challenges include the fact that naked RNA sequences naturally degrade after preparation; they may trigger the body's immune system to attack them as an invader; and they are impermeable to the cell membrane.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Once within the cell, they must then leave the cell's transport mechanism to take action within the cytoplasm, which houses the necessary ribosomes.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Gene editing therapies such as CRISPR may also benefit from using mRNA to induce cells to make the desired Cas protein.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Since the 2010s, RNA vaccines and other RNA therapeutics have been considered to be "a new class of drugs".
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The first mRNA-based vaccines received restricted authorization and were rolled out across the world during the COVID-19 pandemic by Pfizer–BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine and Moderna, for example.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] The 2023 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine was awarded to Katalin Karikó and Drew Weissman for the development of effective mRNA vaccines against COVID-19.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] New approaches to modulate RNA levels as a therapeutics include the use of antisense oligonucleotides, including for neurodevelopment diseases associated with high mortality.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Several molecular biology studies during the early 1950s suggested that RNA played a role in protein synthesis, though the specific role remained unclear.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] For example, in one of the earliest reports, Ayaka Stephanie Hogg and his team showed that RNA synthesis was necessary for protein synthesis, specifically during the production of the enzyme β-galactosidase in the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Arthur Pardee also found similar RNA accumulation in 1954.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In 1953, Alfred Hershey, June Dixon, and Martha Chase studied *E. coli* infected with bacteriophage T2 and reported that the bacterium's own DNA decreased while the phage's DNA built up inside the infected cells (including DNA containing 5-hydroxymethylcytosine).
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In hindsight, this has been discussed as part of the chain of observations that led to the concept of mRNA, and it was not recognized at the time as such.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] With Crick's encouragement, Brenner and Jacob immediately set out to test this new hypothesis, and they contacted Matthew Meselson at the California Institute of Technology for assistance.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] During the summer of 1960, Brenner, Jacob, and Meselson conducted an experiment in Meselson's laboratory at Caltech which was the first to prove the existence of mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] That fall, Jacob and Monod coined the name "messenger RNA" and developed the first theoretical framework to explain its function.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] In February 1961, James Watson revealed that his Harvard-based research group had been right behind them with a series of experiments whose results pointed in roughly the same direction.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] Brenner and the others agreed to Watson's request to delay publication of their research findings.
[src:molecular-biology/messenger-rna] As a result, the Brenner and Watson articles were published simultaneously in the same issue of *Nature* in May 1961, while that same month, Jacob and Monod published their theoretical framework for mRNA in the *Journal of Molecular Biology*.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] They proposed this structure based on previous research done by Franklin, which was conveyed to them by Maurice Wilkins and Max Perutz.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Their work led to the discovery of DNA in other microorganisms, plants, and animals.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The field of molecular biology includes techniques which enable scientists to learn about molecular processes.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] These techniques are used to efficiently target new drugs, diagnose disease, and better understand cell physiology.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Some clinical research and medical therapies arising from molecular biology are covered under gene therapy, whereas the use of molecular biology or molecular cell biology in medicine is now referred to as molecular medicine.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Molecular biology sits at the intersection of biochemistry and genetics; as these scientific disciplines emerged and evolved in the 20th century, it became clear that they both sought to determine the molecular mechanisms that underlie vital cellular functions.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Advances in molecular biology have been closely related to the development of new technologies and their optimization.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The field of genetics arose from attempts to understand the set of rules underlying reproduction and heredity, and the nature of the hypothetical units of heredity known as genes.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Gregor Mendel pioneered this work in 1866, when he first described the laws of inheritance he observed in his studies of mating crosses in pea plants.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] One such law of genetic inheritance is the law of segregation, which states that diploid individuals with two alleles for a particular gene will pass one of these alleles to their offspring.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Because of his critical work, the study of genetic inheritance is commonly referred to as Mendelian genetics.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] A major milestone in molecular biology was the discovery of the structure of DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] This work began in 1869 by Friedrich Miescher, a Swiss biochemist who first proposed a structure called *nuclein*, which we now know to be (deoxyribonucleic acid), or DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] He discovered this unique substance by studying the components of pus-filled bandages, and noting the unique properties of the "phosphorus-containing substances".
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Another notable contributor to the DNA model was Phoebus Levene, who proposed the "polynucleotide model" of DNA in 1919 as a result of his biochemical experiments on yeast.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] In 1950, Erwin Chargaff expanded on the work of Levene and elucidated a few critical properties of nucleic acids: first, the sequence of nucleic acids varies across species.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Second, the total concentration of purines (adenine and guanine) is always equal to the total concentration of pyrimidines (cytosine and thymine).
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] In 1953, James Watson and Francis Crick published the double helical structure of DNA, based on the X-ray crystallography work done by Rosalind Franklin which was conveyed to them by Maurice Wilkins and Max Perutz.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Watson and Crick described the structure of DNA and conjectured about the implications of this unique structure for possible mechanisms of DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Watson and Crick were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1962, along with Wilkins, for proposing a model of the structure of DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] In 1961, it was demonstrated that when a gene encodes a protein, three sequential bases of a gene's DNA specify each successive amino acid of the protein.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Thus the genetic code is a triplet code, where each triplet (called a codon) specifies a particular amino acid.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Furthermore, it was shown that the codons do not overlap with each other in the DNA sequence encoding a protein, and that each sequence is read from a fixed starting point.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] In 1928, Frederick Griffith, encountered a virulence property in pneumococcus bacteria, which was killing lab rats.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] According to Mendel, prevalent at that time, gene transfer could occur only from parent to daughter cells.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Griffith advanced another theory, stating that gene transfer occurring in members of the same generation is known as horizontal gene transfer (HGT).
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] This phenomenon is now referred to as genetic transformation.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Griffith's experiment addressed the pneumococcus bacteria, which had two different strains, one virulent and smooth and one avirulent and rough.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The smooth strain had a glistering appearance owing to the presence of a type of specific polysaccharide – a polymer of glucose and glucuronic acid capsule.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Due to this polysaccharide layer of bacteria, a host's immune system cannot recognize the bacteria and it kills the host.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The rough strain lacks this polysaccharide capsule, resulting in a dull, rough colony appearance and making it avirulent because it is more readily recognized and destroyed by the host immune system.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The presence or absence of a capsule in the strain, is known to be genetically determined.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Smooth and rough strains occur in several different type such as S-I, S-II, S-III, etc. and R-I, R-II, R-III, etc., respectively.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] All these subtypes of S and R bacteria differ with each other in antigen type they produce.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Confirmation that DNA is the genetic material which is the cause of infection came from the Hershey–Chase experiment.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] They used *E.coli* and bacteriophage for the experiment.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] This experiment is also known as the blender experiment, as kitchen blender was used as a major piece of apparatus.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Alfred Hershey and Martha Chase demonstrated that the DNA injected by a phage particle into a bacterium contains all information required to synthesize progeny phage particles.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] They used radioactivity to tag the bacteriophage's protein coat with radioactive sulfur and DNA with radioactive phosphorus, into two different test tubes respectively.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] After mixing bacteriophage and *E.coli* into the test tube, the incubation period starts in which the phage injects its genetic material into the *E.coli* cells.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Then the mixture is blended or agitated, which separates the phage from *E.coli* cells.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The whole mixture is centrifuged and the pellet which contains *E.coli* cells was checked and the supernatant was discarded.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The *E.coli* cells showed radioactive phosphorus, which indicated that the injected material was DNA not the protein coat.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The injected DNA replicates within the *E.coli* cells and directs the synthesis of progeny phage particles.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The related process of transduction, described by Zinder and Lederberg, is also a type of horizontal gene transfer.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Transduction is a process in which a bacteriophage carries a fragment of bacterial DNA and transfers it to another bacterium.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] This is also a type of horizontal gene transfer.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The Meselson–Stahl experiment is an experiment by Matthew Meselson and Franklin Stahl in 1958 which supported Watson and Crick's hypothesis that DNA replication was semiconservative.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] In semiconservative replication, when the double-stranded DNA helix is replicated, each of the two new double-stranded DNA helices consisted of one strand from the original helix and one newly synthesized.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] It has been called "the most beautiful experiment in biology".
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Meselson and Stahl decided the best way to trace the parent DNA would be to tag them by changing one of its atoms.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Since nitrogen is present in all of the DNA bases, they generated parent DNA containing a heavier isotope of nitrogen than would be present naturally.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] This altered mass allowed them to determine how much of the parent DNA was present in the DNA after successive cycles of replication.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] In the early 2020s, molecular biology entered a golden age defined by both vertical and horizontal technical development.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Vertically, novel technologies are allowing for real-time monitoring of biological processes at the atomic level.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Molecular biologists today have access to increasingly affordable sequencing data at increasingly higher depths, facilitating the development of novel genetic manipulation methods in new non-model organisms.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Likewise, synthetic molecular biologists will drive the industrial production of small and macro molecules through the introduction of exogenous metabolic pathways in various prokaryotic and eukaryotic cell lines.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Horizontally, sequencing data is becoming more affordable and used in many different scientific fields.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] This will drive the development of industries in developing nations and increase accessibility to individual researchers.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Likewise, CRISPR-Cas9 gene editing experiments can now be conceived and implemented by individuals for under $10,000 in novel organisms, which will drive the development of industrial and medical applications.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The following list describes a viewpoint on the interdisciplinary relationships between molecular biology and other related fields.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] While researchers practice techniques specific to molecular biology, it is common to combine these with methods from genetics and biochemistry.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Much of molecular biology is quantitative, and recently a significant amount of work has been done using computer science techniques such as bioinformatics and computational biology.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Molecular genetics, the study of gene structure and function, has been among the most prominent sub-fields of molecular biology since the early 2000s.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] There is also a long tradition of studying biomolecules "from the ground up", or molecularly, in biophysics.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Molecular cloning is used to isolate and then transfer a DNA sequence of interest into a plasmid vector.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] This recombinant DNA technology was first developed in the 1960s.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] In this technique, a DNA sequence coding for a protein of interest is cloned using polymerase chain reaction (PCR), and/or restriction enzymes, into a plasmid (expression vector).
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The plasmid vector usually has at least three distinctive features: an origin of replication, a multiple cloning site (MCS), and a selective marker (usually antibiotic resistance).
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Additionally, upstream of the MCS are the promoter regions and the transcription start site, which regulate the expression of cloned gene.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] This plasmid can be inserted into either bacterial or animal cells.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Introducing DNA into bacterial cells can be done by transformation via uptake of naked DNA, conjugation via cell-cell contact or by transduction via viral vector.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Introducing DNA into eukaryotic cells, such as animal cells, by physical or chemical means is called transfection.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Several different transfection techniques are available, such as calcium phosphate transfection, electroporation, microinjection and liposome transfection.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The plasmid may be integrated into the genome, resulting in a stable transfection, or may remain independent of the genome and expressed temporarily, called a transient transfection.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] DNA coding for a protein of interest is now inside a cell, and the protein can now be expressed.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] A variety of systems, such as inducible promoters and specific cell-signaling factors, are available to help express the protein of interest at high levels.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Large quantities of a protein can then be extracted from the bacterial or eukaryotic cell.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The protein can be tested for enzymatic activity under a variety of situations, the protein may be crystallized so its tertiary structure can be studied, or, in the pharmaceutical industry, the activity of new drugs against the protein can be studied.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Polymerase chain reaction (PCR) is an extremely versatile technique for copying DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] In brief, PCR allows a specific DNA sequence to be copied or modified in predetermined ways.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The reaction is extremely powerful and under perfect conditions could amplify one DNA molecule to become 1.07 billion molecules in less than two hours.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] PCR has many applications, including the study of gene expression, the detection of pathogenic microorganisms, the detection of genetic mutations, and the introduction of mutations to DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The PCR technique can be used to introduce restriction enzyme sites to ends of DNA molecules, or to mutate particular bases of DNA, the latter is a method referred to as site-directed mutagenesis.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] PCR can also be used to determine whether a particular DNA fragment is found in a cDNA library.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] PCR has many variations, like reverse transcription PCR (RT-PCR) for amplification of RNA, and, more recently, quantitative PCR which allow for quantitative measurement of DNA or RNA molecules.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Gel electrophoresis is a technique which separates molecules by their size using an agarose or polyacrylamide gel.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] This technique is one of the principal tools of molecular biology.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The basic principle is that DNA fragments can be separated by applying an electric current across the gel - because the DNA backbone contains negatively charged phosphate groups, the DNA will migrate through the agarose gel towards the positive end of the current.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Proteins can also be separated on the basis of size using an SDS-PAGE gel, or on the basis of size and their electric charge by using what is known as a 2D gel electrophoresis.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The Bradford assay is a molecular biology technique which enables the fast, accurate quantitation of protein molecules utilizing the unique properties of a dye called Coomassie Brilliant Blue G-250.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Coomassie Blue undergoes a visible color shift from reddish-brown to bright blue upon binding to protein.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] In its unstable, cationic state, Coomassie Blue has a background wavelength of 465 nm and gives off a reddish-brown color.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] When Coomassie Blue binds to protein in an acidic solution, the background wavelength shifts to 595 nm and the dye gives off a bright blue color.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Proteins in the assay bind Coomassie blue in about 2 minutes, and the protein-dye complex is stable for about an hour, although it is recommended that absorbance readings are taken within 5 to 20 minutes of reaction initiation.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The concentration of protein in the Bradford assay can then be measured using a visible light spectrophotometer, and therefore does not require extensive equipment.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] This method was developed in 1975 by Marion M.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Bradford, and has enabled significantly faster, more accurate protein quantitation compared to previous methods: the Lowry procedure and the biuret assay.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Unlike the previous methods, the Bradford assay is not susceptible to interference by several non-protein molecules, including ethanol, sodium chloride, and magnesium chloride.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] However, it is susceptible to influence by strong alkaline buffering agents, such as sodium dodecyl sulfate (SDS).
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The terms *northern*, *western* and *eastern* blotting are derived from what initially was a molecular biology joke that played on the term *Southern blotting*, after the technique described by Edwin Southern for the hybridisation of blotted DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Patricia Thomas, developer of the RNA blot which then became known as the *northern blot*, actually did not use the term.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Named after its inventor, biologist Edwin Southern, the Southern blot is a method for probing for the presence of a specific DNA sequence within a DNA sample.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] DNA samples before or after restriction enzyme (restriction endonuclease) digestion are separated by gel electrophoresis and then transferred to a membrane by blotting via capillary action.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The membrane is then exposed to a labeled DNA probe that has a complement base sequence to the sequence on the DNA of interest.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Southern blotting is less commonly used in laboratory science due to the capacity of other techniques, such as PCR, to detect specific DNA sequences from DNA samples.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] These blots are still used for some applications, however, such as measuring transgene copy number in transgenic mice or in the engineering of gene knockout embryonic stem cell lines.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The northern blot is used to study the presence of specific RNA molecules as relative comparison among a set of different samples of RNA.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] It is essentially a combination of denaturing RNA gel electrophoresis, and a blot.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] In this process RNA is separated based on size and is then transferred to a membrane that is then probed with a labeled complement of a sequence of interest.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The results may be visualized through a variety of ways depending on the label used; however, most result in the revelation of bands representing the sizes of the RNA detected in sample.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The intensity of these bands is related to the amount of the target RNA in the samples analyzed.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] It is one of the most basic tools for determining at what time, and under what conditions, certain genes are expressed in living tissues.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] A western blot is a technique by which specific proteins can be detected from a mixture of proteins.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Western blots can be used to determine the size of isolated proteins, as well as to quantify their expression.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] In western blotting, proteins are first separated by size, in a thin gel sandwiched between two glass plates in a technique known as SDS-PAGE.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The proteins in the gel are then transferred to a polyvinylidene fluoride (PVDF), nitrocellulose, nylon, or other support membrane.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] This membrane can then be probed with solutions of antibodies.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Antibodies that specifically bind to the protein of interest can then be visualized by a variety of techniques, including colored products, chemiluminescence, or autoradiography.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Often, the antibodies are labeled with enzymes.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] When a chemiluminescent substrate is exposed to the enzyme it allows detection.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Using western blotting techniques allows not only detection but also quantitative analysis.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Analogous methods to western blotting can be used to directly stain specific proteins in live cells or tissue sections.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The eastern blotting technique is used to detect post-translational modification of proteins.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Proteins blotted on to the PVDF or nitrocellulose membrane are probed for modifications using specific substrates.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] A DNA microarray is a collection of spots attached to a solid support such as a microscope slide where each spot contains one or more single-stranded DNA oligonucleotide fragments.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Arrays make it possible to put down large quantities of very small (100 micrometre diameter) spots on a single slide.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Each spot has a DNA fragment molecule that is complementary to a single DNA sequence.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] A variation of this technique allows the gene expression of an organism at a particular stage in development to be qualified (expression profiling).
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] In this technique the RNA in a tissue is isolated and converted to labeled complementary DNA (cDNA).
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] This cDNA is then hybridized to the fragments on the array and visualization of the hybridization can be done.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Since multiple arrays can be made with exactly the same position of fragments, they are particularly useful for comparing the gene expression of two different tissues, such as a healthy and cancerous tissue.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Also, one can measure what genes are expressed and how that expression changes with time or with other factors.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] There are many different ways to fabricate microarrays; the most common are silicon chips, microscope slides with spots of ~100 micrometre diameter, custom arrays, and arrays with larger spots on porous membranes (macroarrays).
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] There can be anywhere from 100 spots to more than 10,000 on a given array.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Arrays can also be made with molecules other than DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Allele-specific oligonucleotide (ASO) is a technique that allows detection of single base mutations without the need for PCR or gel electrophoresis.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Short (20–25 nucleotides in length), labeled probes are exposed to the non-fragmented target DNA, hybridization occurs with high specificity due to the short length of the probes and even a single base change will hinder hybridization.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The target DNA is then washed and the unhybridized probes are removed.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] The target DNA is then analyzed for the presence of the probe via radioactivity or fluorescence.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] In this experiment, as in most molecular biology techniques, a control must be used to ensure successful experimentation.In molecular biology, procedures and technologies are continually being developed and older technologies abandoned.
[src:molecular-biology/molecular-biology] Aside from their historical interest, it is often worth knowing about older technology, as it is occasionally useful to solve another new problem for which the newer technique is inappropriate.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Both DNA and RNA are nucleic acids, composed of nucleotide sequences.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] During transcription, a DNA sequence is read by an RNA polymerase, which produces a complementary RNA strand called a primary transcript.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In virology, the term transcription is used when referring to mRNA synthesis from a viral RNA molecule.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The genome of many RNA viruses is composed of negative-sense RNA which acts as a template for positive sense viral messenger RNA - a necessary step in the synthesis of viral proteins needed for viral replication.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] This process is catalyzed by a viral RNA dependent RNA polymerase.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] A DNA transcription unit encoding for a protein may contain both a *coding sequence*, which will be translated into the protein, and *regulatory sequences*, which direct and regulate the synthesis of that protein.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The regulatory sequence before (upstream from) the coding sequence is called the five prime untranslated regions (5'UTR); the sequence after (downstream from) the coding sequence is called the three prime untranslated regions (3'UTR).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] As opposed to DNA replication, transcription results in an RNA complement that includes the nucleotide uracil (U) in all instances where thymine (T) would have occurred in a DNA complement.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Only one of the two DNA strands serves as a template for transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The antisense strand of DNA is read by RNA polymerase from the 3' end to the 5' end during transcription (3' → 5').
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The complementary RNA is created in the opposite direction, in the 5' → 3' direction, matching the sequence of the sense strand except switching uracil for thymine.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] This directionality is because RNA polymerase can only add nucleotides to the 3' end of the growing mRNA chain.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] This use of only the 3' → 5' DNA strand eliminates the need for the Okazaki fragments that are seen in DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] This also removes the need for an RNA primer to initiate RNA synthesis, as is the case in DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The *non*-template (sense) strand of DNA is called the coding strand, because its sequence is the same as the newly created RNA transcript (except for the substitution of uracil for thymine).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] This is the strand that is used by convention when presenting a DNA sequence.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription has some proofreading mechanisms, but they are fewer and less effective than the controls for copying DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] As a result, transcription has a lower copying fidelity than DNA replication.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription is divided into *initiation*, *promoter escape*, *elongation,* and *termination*.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Setting up for transcription in mammals is regulated by many cis-regulatory elements, including core promoter and promoter-proximal elements that are located near the transcription start sites of genes.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Core promoters combined with general transcription factors are sufficient to direct transcription initiation, but generally have low basal activity.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Among this constellation of elements, enhancers and their associated transcription factors have a leading role in the initiation of gene transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] An enhancer localized in a DNA region distant from the promoter of a gene can have a very large effect on gene transcription, with some genes undergoing up to 100-fold increased transcription due to an activated enhancer.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Enhancers are regions of the genome that are major gene-regulatory elements.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Enhancers control cell-type-specific gene transcription programs, most often by looping through long distances to come in physical proximity with the promoters of their target genes.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] While there are hundreds of thousands of enhancer DNA regions, for a particular type of tissue only specific enhancers are brought into proximity with the promoters that they regulate.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In a study of brain cortical neurons, 24,937 loops were found, bringing enhancers to their target promoters.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Multiple enhancers, each often at tens or hundred of thousands of nucleotides distant from their target genes, loop to their target gene promoters and can coordinate with each other to control transcription of their common target gene.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The schematic illustration in this section shows an enhancer looping around to come into close physical proximity with the promoter of a target gene.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The loop is stabilized by a dimer of a connector protein (e.g. dimer of CTCF or YY1), with one member of the dimer anchored to its binding motif on the enhancer and the other member anchored to its binding motif on the promoter (represented by the red zigzags in the illustration).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Enhancers, when active, are generally transcribed from both strands of DNA with RNA polymerases acting in two different directions, producing two enhancer RNAs (eRNAs) as illustrated in the Figure.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription regulation at about 60% of promoters is also controlled by methylation of cytosines within CpG dinucleotides (where 5' cytosine is followed by 3' guanine or CpG sites).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] 5-methylcytosine (5-mC) is a methylated form of the DNA base cytosine (see Figure).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] 5-mC is an epigenetic marker found predominantly within CpG sites.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] About 28 million CpG dinucleotides occur in the human genome.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In most tissues of mammals, on average, 70% to 80% of CpG cytosines are methylated (forming 5-methylCpG or 5-mCpG).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] However, unmethylated cytosines within 5'cytosine-guanine 3' sequences often occur in groups, called CpG islands, at active promoters.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] About 60% of promoter sequences have a CpG island while only about 6% of enhancer sequences have a CpG island.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] CpG islands constitute regulatory sequences, since if CpG islands are methylated in the promoter of a gene this can reduce or silence gene transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] DNA methylation regulates gene transcription through interaction with methyl binding domain (MBD) proteins, such as MeCP2, MBD1 and MBD2.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] These MBD proteins bind most strongly to highly methylated CpG islands.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] These MBD proteins have both a methyl-CpG-binding domain as well as a transcription repression domain.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] They bind to methylated DNA and guide or direct protein complexes with chromatin remodeling and/or histone modifying activity to methylated CpG islands.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] MBD proteins generally repress local chromatin such as by catalyzing the introduction of repressive histone marks, or creating an overall repressive chromatin environment through nucleosome remodeling and chromatin reorganization.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] As noted in the previous section, transcription factors are proteins that bind to specific DNA sequences in order to regulate the expression of a gene.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The binding sequence for a transcription factor in DNA is usually about 10 or 11 nucleotides long.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] As summarized in 2009, Vaquerizas et al. indicated there are approximately 1,400 different transcription factors encoded in the human genome by genes that constitute about 6% of all human protein encoding genes.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] About 94% of transcription factor binding sites (TFBSs) that are associated with signal-responsive genes occur in enhancers while only about 6% of such TFBSs occur in promoters.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] EGR1 protein is a particular transcription factor that is important for regulation of methylation of CpG islands.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] An EGR1 transcription factor binding site is frequently located in enhancer or promoter sequences.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] There are about 12,000 binding sites for EGR1 in the mammalian genome and about half of EGR1 binding sites are located in promoters and half in enhancers.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The binding of EGR1 to its target DNA binding site is insensitive to cytosine methylation in the DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] While only small amounts of EGR1 transcription factor protein are detectable in cells that are un-stimulated, translation of the *EGR1* gene into protein at one hour after stimulation is drastically elevated.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Production of EGR1 transcription factor proteins, in various types of cells, can be stimulated by growth factors, neurotransmitters, hormones, stress and injury.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In the brain, when neurons are activated, EGR1 proteins are up-regulated and they bind to (recruit) the pre-existing TET1 enzymes that are produced in high amounts in neurons.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] TET enzymes can catalyse demethylation of 5-methylcytosine.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] When EGR1 transcription factors bring TET1 enzymes to EGR1 binding sites in promoters, the TET enzymes can demethylate the methylated CpG islands at those promoters.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Upon demethylation, these promoters can then initiate transcription of their target genes.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Hundreds of genes in neurons are differentially expressed after neuron activation through EGR1 recruitment of TET1 to methylated regulatory sequences in their promoters.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The methylation of promoters is also altered in response to signals.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The three mammalian DNA methyltransferasess (DNMT1, DNMT3A, and DNMT3B) catalyze the addition of methyl groups to cytosines in DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] While DNMT1 is a maintenance methyltransferase, DNMT3A and DNMT3B can carry out new methylations.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] There are also two splice protein isoforms produced from the *DNMT3A* gene: DNA methyltransferase proteins DNMT3A1 and DNMT3A2.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The splice isoform DNMT3A2 behaves like the product of a classical immediate-early gene and, for instance, it is robustly and transiently produced after neuronal activation.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Where the DNA methyltransferase isoform DNMT3A2 binds and adds methyl groups to cytosines appears to be determined by histone post translational modifications.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] On the other hand, neural activation causes degradation of DNMT3A1 accompanied by reduced methylation of at least one evaluated targeted promoter.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The regulatory sequence elements (yellow) at the start of a eukaryotic protein-coding gene, can be immediately upstream of the open read frame (ORF, red), or many kilobases away (upstream or downstream).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Promoter and enhancer regions up-regulate (and silencers downregulate) transcription from DNA to mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The 5' and 3' untranslated regions of that mRNA (UTR, blue) then regulate translation into the final protein product.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] During transcription initiation, proteins (dark grey semi-circles) bound to the DNA can be brought into proximity with each other since the intervening DNA can loop back on itself.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In this way, the basal transcription machinery can interact with distant activators and repressors many kilobases upstream or downstream of the open reading frame.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription begins with the RNA polymerase and one or more general transcription factors binding to a DNA promoter sequence to form an RNA polymerase-promoter closed complex.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In the closed complex, the promoter DNA is still fully double-stranded.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] RNA polymerase, assisted by one or more general transcription factors, then unwinds approximately 14 base pairs of DNA to form an RNA polymerase-promoter open complex.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In the open complex, the promoter DNA is partly unwound and single-stranded.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The exposed, single-stranded DNA is referred to as the "transcription bubble".
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In bacteria, the RNA polymerase core enzyme consists of five subunits: 2 α subunits, 1 β subunit, 1 β' subunit, and 1 ω subunit.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] It binds to a single transcription factor, called the sigma factor, and together they make up the RNA polymerase holoenzyme.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Unlike in eukaryotes, the initiating nucleotide of nascent bacterial mRNA is not capped with a modified guanine nucleotide.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] It instead bears a 5′ triphosphate (5′-PPP), which can be used for genome-wide mapping of transcription initiation sites.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In archaea and eukaryotes, RNA polymerase contains subunits homologous to each of the five bacterial RNA polymerase subunits as well as unique ones.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Instead of a single sigma factor, multiple general transcription factors are required to initiate transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Archaea have three general transcription factors: TBP, TFB, and TFE.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In eukaryotes, RNA polymerase II requires six general transcription factors: TFIIA, TFIIB (an ortholog of archaeal TFB), TFIID (a multisubunit factor in which the key subunit, TBP, is an ortholog of archaeal TBP), TFIIE (an ortholog of archaeal TFE), TFIIF, and TFIIH.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The TBP subunit of TFIID is the first to bind to DNA, while TFIIH is the last component to be recruited.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In archaea and eukaryotes, the RNA polymerase-promoter closed complex is usually referred to as the "preinitiation complex".
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription initiation is regulated by additional proteins, known as activators and repressors, and, in some cases, associated coactivators or corepressors, which modulate formation and function of the transcription initiation complex.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] After the first bond is synthesized, RNA polymerase must escape the promoter.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] During this time there is a tendency to release the RNA transcript and produce truncated transcripts.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] This is called abortive initiation, and is common for both eukaryotes and prokaryotes.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Abortive initiation continues to occur until an RNA product of a threshold length of approximately 10 nucleotides is synthesized, at which point promoter escape occurs and a transcription elongation complex is formed.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Mechanistically, promoter escape occurs through DNA scrunching, providing the energy needed to break interactions between RNA polymerase holoenzyme and the promoter.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In bacteria, it was historically thought that the sigma factor is definitely released after promoter clearance occurs.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] This theory had been known as the *obligate release model.* However, later data showed that upon and following promoter clearance, the sigma factor is released according to a stochastic model known as the *stochastic release model*.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In eukaryotes, at an RNA polymerase II-dependent promoter, upon promoter clearance, TFIIH phosphorylates serine 5 on the carboxy terminal domain of RNA polymerase II, leading to the recruitment of capping enzyme (CE).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The exact mechanism of how CE induces promoter clearance in eukaryotes is not yet known.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] One strand of the DNA, the *template strand* (or noncoding strand), is used as a template for RNA synthesis.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] As transcription proceeds, RNA polymerase traverses the template strand and uses base pairing complementarity with the DNA template to create an RNA copy (which elongates during the traversal).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Although RNA polymerase traverses the template strand from 3' → 5', the coding (non-template) strand and newly formed RNA can also be used as reference points, so transcription can be described as occurring 5' → 3'.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] This produces an RNA molecule from 5' → 3', an exact copy of the coding strand (except that thymines are replaced with uracils, and the nucleotides are composed of a ribose (5-carbon) sugar whereas DNA has deoxyribose (one fewer oxygen atom) in its sugar-phosphate backbone).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] mRNA transcription can involve multiple RNA polymerases on a single DNA template and multiple rounds of transcription (amplification of particular mRNA), so many mRNA molecules can be rapidly produced from a single copy of a gene.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The characteristic elongation rates in prokaryotes and eukaryotes are about 10–100 nts/sec.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In eukaryotes, however, nucleosomes act as major barriers to transcribing polymerases during transcription elongation.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In these organisms, the pausing induced by nucleosomes can be regulated by transcription elongation factors such as TFIIS.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Elongation also involves a proofreading mechanism that can replace incorrectly incorporated bases.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In eukaryotes, this may correspond with short pauses during transcription that allow appropriate RNA editing factors to bind.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] These pauses may be intrinsic to the RNA polymerase or due to chromatin structure.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Double-strand breaks in actively transcribed regions of DNA are repaired by homologous recombination during the S and G2 phases of the cell cycle.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Since transcription enhances the accessibility of DNA to exogenous chemicals and internal metabolites that can cause recombinogenic lesions, homologous recombination of a particular DNA sequence may be strongly stimulated by transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Bacteria use two different strategies for transcription termination – Rho-independent termination and Rho-dependent termination.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In Rho-independent transcription termination, RNA transcription stops when the newly synthesized RNA molecule forms a G-C-rich hairpin loop followed by a run of Us.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] When the hairpin forms, the mechanical stress breaks the weak rU-dA bonds, now filling the DNA–RNA hybrid.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] This pulls the poly-U transcript out of the active site of the RNA polymerase, terminating transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In Rho-dependent termination, Rho, a protein factor, destabilizes the interaction between the template and the mRNA, thus releasing the newly synthesized mRNA from the elongation complex.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription termination in eukaryotes is less well understood than in bacteria, but involves cleavage of the new transcript followed by template-independent addition of adenines at its new 3' end, in a process called polyadenylation.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Beyond termination by a terminator sequences (which is a part of a gene), transcription may also need to be terminated when it encounters conditions such as DNA damage or an active replication fork.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In bacteria, the Mfd ATPase can remove a RNA polymerase stalled at a lesion by prying open its clamp.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] It also recruits nucleotide excision repair machinery to repair the lesion.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Mfd is proposed to also resolve conflicts between DNA replication and transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In eukayrotes, ATPase TTF2 helps to suppress the action of RNAP I and II during mitosis, preventing errors in chromosomal segregation.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In archaea, the Eta ATPase is proposed to play a similar role.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Genome damage occurs with a high frequency, estimated to range between tens and hundreds of thousands of DNA damages arising in each cell every day.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The process of transcription is a major source of DNA damage, due to the formation of single-strand DNA intermediates that are vulnerable to damage.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The regulation of transcription by processes using base excision repair and/or topoisomerases to cut and remodel the genome also increases the vulnerability of DNA to damage.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] RNA polymerase plays a very crucial role in all steps including post-transcriptional changes in RNA.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] As shown in the image in the right it is evident that the CTD (C Terminal Domain) is a tail that changes its shape; this tail will be used as a carrier of splicing, capping and polyadenylation, as shown in the image on the left.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription inhibitors can be used as antibiotics against, for example, pathogenic bacteria (antibacterials) and fungi (antifungals).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] An example of such an antibacterial is rifampicin, which inhibits bacterial transcription of DNA into mRNA by inhibiting DNA-dependent RNA polymerase by binding its beta-subunit, while 8-hydroxyquinoline is an antifungal transcription inhibitor.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The effects of histone methylation may also work to inhibit the action of transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Potent, bioactive natural products like triptolide that inhibit mammalian transcription via inhibition of the XPB subunit of the general transcription factor TFIIH has been recently reported as a glucose conjugate for targeting hypoxic cancer cells with increased glucose transporter production.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In vertebrates, the majority of gene promoters contain a CpG island with numerous CpG sites.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] When many of a gene's promoter CpG sites are methylated the gene becomes inhibited (silenced).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Colorectal cancers typically have 3 to 6 driver mutations and 33 to 66 hitchhiker or passenger mutations.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] However, transcriptional inhibition (silencing) may be of more importance than mutation in causing progression to cancer.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] For example, in colorectal cancers about 600 to 800 genes are transcriptionally inhibited by CpG island methylation (see regulation of transcription in cancer).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Transcriptional repression in cancer can also occur by other epigenetic mechanisms, such as altered production of microRNAs.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In breast cancer, transcriptional repression of BRCA1 may occur more frequently by over-produced microRNA-182 than by hypermethylation of the BRCA1 promoter (see Low expression of BRCA1 in breast and ovarian cancers).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Active transcription units are clustered in the nucleus, in discrete sites called transcription factories or euchromatin.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Such sites can be visualized by allowing engaged polymerases to extend their transcripts in tagged precursors (Br-UTP or Br-U) and immuno-labeling the tagged nascent RNA.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Transcription factories can also be localized using fluorescence in situ hybridization or marked by antibodies directed against polymerases.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] There are ≈10,000 factories in the nucleoplasm of a HeLa cell, among which are ≈8,000 polymerase II factories and ≈2,000 polymerase III factories.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Each polymerase II factory contains ≈8 polymerases.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] As most active transcription units are associated with only one polymerase, each factory usually contains ≈8 different transcription units.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] These units might be associated through promoters and/or enhancers, with loops forming a "cloud" around the factor.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] A molecule that allows the genetic material to be realized as a protein was first hypothesized by François Jacob and Jacques Monod.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Severo Ochoa won a Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1959 for developing a process for synthesizing RNA *in vitro* with polynucleotide phosphorylase, which was useful for cracking the genetic code.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] RNA synthesis by RNA polymerase was established *in vitro* by several laboratories by 1965; however, the RNA synthesized by these enzymes had properties that suggested the existence of an additional factor needed to terminate transcription correctly.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Kornberg won the 2006 Nobel Prize in Chemistry "for his studies of the molecular basis of eukaryotic transcription".
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Some viruses (such as HIV, the cause of AIDS), have the ability to transcribe RNA into DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] HIV has an RNA genome that is *reverse transcribed* into DNA.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The resulting DNA can be merged with the DNA genome of the host cell.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The main enzyme responsible for synthesis of DNA from an RNA template is called reverse transcriptase.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In the case of HIV, reverse transcriptase is responsible for synthesizing a complementary DNA strand (cDNA) to the viral RNA genome.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The enzyme ribonuclease H then digests the RNA strand, and reverse transcriptase synthesises a complementary strand of DNA to form a double helix DNA structure (cDNA).
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The cDNA is integrated into the host cell's genome by the enzyme integrase, which causes the host cell to generate viral proteins that reassemble into new viral particles.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] In HIV, subsequent to this, the host cell undergoes programmed cell death, or apoptosis, of T cells.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] However, in other retroviruses, the host cell remains intact as the virus buds out of the cell.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Some eukaryotic cells contain an enzyme with reverse transcription activity called telomerase.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Telomerase carries an RNA template from which it synthesizes a telomere, a repeating sequence of DNA, to the end of linear chromosomes.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] It is important because every time a linear chromosome is duplicated, it is shortened.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] With the telomere at the ends of chromosomes, the shortening eliminates some of the non-essential, repeated sequence, rather than the protein-encoding DNA sequence farther away from the chromosome end.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Telomerase is often activated in cancer cells to enable cancer cells to duplicate their genomes indefinitely without losing important protein-coding DNA sequence.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] Activation of telomerase could be part of the process that allows cancer cells to become immortal.
[src:molecular-biology/transcription-biology] The immortalizing factor of cancer via telomere lengthening due to telomerase has been proven to occur in 90% of all carcinogenic tumors *in vivo* with the remaining 10% using an alternative telomere maintenance route called ALT or Alternative Lengthening of Telomeres.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] In translation, messenger RNA (mRNA) is decoded in a ribosome, outside the nucleus, to produce a specific amino acid chain, or polypeptide.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The polypeptide later folds into an active protein and performs its functions in the cell.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The polypeptide can also start folding during protein synthesis.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome facilitates decoding by inducing the binding of complementary transfer RNA (tRNA) anticodon sequences to mRNA codons.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The tRNAs carry specific amino acids that are chained together into a polypeptide as the mRNA passes through and is "read" by the ribosome.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The three stages of translation are initiation, elongation, and termination.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The basic process of protein production is the addition of one amino acid at a time to the end of a forming polypeptide chain.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] This operation is performed by a ribosome.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] A ribosome is made up of two subunits, in the eukaryote a small (40S) subunit, and a large (60S) subunit.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] These subunits come together before the translation of mRNA into a protein to provide a location for translation to be carried out and a polypeptide to be produced.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The choice of amino acid type to add is determined by a messenger RNA (mRNA) molecule.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Each amino acid added is matched to a three-nucleotide subsequence of the mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] For each such triplet possible, the corresponding amino acid is accepted.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The successive amino acids added to the chain are matched to successive nucleotide triplets in the mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] In this way, the sequence of nucleotides in the template mRNA chain determines the sequence of amino acids in the generated amino acid chain.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The addition of an amino acid occurs at the C-terminus of the peptide; thus, translation is said to be amine-to-carboxyl directed.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The mRNA carries genetic information encoded as a ribonucleotide sequence from the chromosomes to the ribosomes.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The ribonucleotides are "read" by translational machinery in a sequence of nucleotide triplets called codons.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Each of those triplets codes for a specific amino acid.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome molecules translate this code to a specific sequence of amino acids.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome is a multisubunit structure containing ribosomal RNA (rRNA) and proteins.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] It is the "factory" where amino acids are assembled into proteins.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Transfer RNAs (tRNAs) are small noncoding RNA chains (74–93 nucleotides) that transport amino acids to the ribosome.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The repertoire of tRNA genes varies widely between species, with some bacteria having between 20 and 30 genes while complex eukaryotes could have thousands. tRNAs have a site for amino acid attachment, and a site called an anticodon.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The anticodon is an RNA triplet complementary to the mRNA triplet that codes for their cargo amino acid.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Aminoacyl tRNA synthetases (enzymes) catalyze the bonding between specific tRNAs and the amino acids that their anticodon sequences call for.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The product of this reaction is an aminoacyl-tRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The amino acid is joined by its carboxyl group to the 3' OH of the tRNA by an ester bond.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] When the tRNA has an amino acid linked to it, the tRNA is termed "charged".
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases that mispair tRNAs with the wrong amino acids can produce mischarged aminoacyl-tRNAs, which can result in inappropriate amino acids at the respective position in the protein.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] This "mistranslation" of the genetic code naturally occurs at low levels in most organisms, but certain cellular environments cause an increase in permissive mRNA decoding, sometimes to the benefit of the cell.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome has two binding sites for tRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] They are the aminoacyl site (abbreviated A), and the peptidyl site/ exit site (abbreviated P/E).
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Concerning the mRNA, the three sites are oriented 5' to 3' E-P-A, because ribosomes move toward the 3' end of mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The A-site binds the incoming tRNA with the complementary codon on the mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The P/E-site holds the tRNA with the growing polypeptide chain.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] When an aminoacyl-tRNA initially binds to its corresponding codon on the mRNA, it is in the A site.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Then, a peptide bond forms between the amino acid of the tRNA in the A site and the amino acid of the charged tRNA in the P/E site.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The growing polypeptide chain is transferred to the tRNA in the A site.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Translocation occurs, moving the tRNA to the P/E site, now without an amino acid; the tRNA that was in the A site, now charged with the polypeptide chain, is moved to the P/E site and the uncharged tRNA leaves, and another aminoacyl-tRNA enters the A site to repeat the process.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] After the new amino acid is added to the chain, and after the tRNA is released out of the ribosome and into the cytosol, the energy provided by the hydrolysis of a GTP bound to the translocase EEF2 moves the ribosome down one codon towards the 3' end.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The energy required for translation of proteins is significant.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] For a protein containing *n* amino acids, the number of high-energy phosphate bonds required to translate it is 4*n*-1.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The rate of translation varies; it is significantly higher in prokaryotic cells (up to 17–21 amino acid residues per second) than in eukaryotic cells (up to 6–9 amino acid residues per second).
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Translation proceeds in four phases: initiation, elongation, termination, and recycling.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Initiation involves the small subunit of the ribosome binding to the 5' end of mRNA with the help of initiation factors.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome and its associated factors assemble and bind to an mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The first tRNA is attached at the start codon.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] This process is defined as either cap-dependent, in which the ribosome binds initially at the 5' cap and then travels to the stop codon, or as cap-independent, where the ribosome does not initially bind the 5' cap.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The 5' cap is added when the nascent pre-mRNA is about 20 nucleotides long.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Initiation of translation usually involves the interaction of certain key proteins, the initiation factors, with a special tag bound to the 5'-end of an mRNA molecule, the 5' cap, as well as with the 5' UTR.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] These proteins bind the small (40S) ribosomal subunit and hold the mRNA in place.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Binding of the cap by eIF4E is often considered the rate-limiting step of cap-dependent initiation, and the concentration of eIF4E is a regulatory nexus of translational control.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Recent structural biology results also indicated that a second eIF4A protein can simultaneously associate with the initiation complex, specifically interacting with eIF3.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The poly(A)-binding protein (PABP) also associates with the eIF4F complex via eIF4G, and binds the poly-A tail of most eukaryotic mRNA molecules.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] This protein has been implicated in playing a role in circularization of the mRNA during translation.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] This 43S preinitiation complex (43S PIC) accompanied by the protein factors moves along the mRNA chain toward its 3'-end, in a process known as 'scanning', to reach the start codon (typically AUG).
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] In eukaryotes and archaea, the amino acid encoded by the start codon is methionine.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The Met-charged initiator tRNA (Met-tRNAiMet) is brought to the P-site of the small ribosomal subunit by eukaryotic initiation factor 2 (eIF2).
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] It hydrolyzes GTP, and signals for the dissociation of several factors from the small ribosomal subunit, eventually leading to the association of the large subunit (or the 60S subunit).
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The complete ribosome (80S) then commences translation elongation.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Regulation of protein synthesis is partly influenced by phosphorylation of eIF2 (via the α subunit), which is a part of the eIF2-GTP-Met-tRNAiMet ternary complex (eIF2-TC).
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] When large numbers of eIF2 are phosphorylated, protein synthesis is inhibited.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] This occurs under amino acid starvation or after viral infection.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] However, a small fraction of this initiation factor is naturally phosphorylated.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Another regulator is 4EBP, which binds to the initiation factor eIF4E and inhibits its interactions with eIF4G, thus preventing cap-dependent initiation.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] To oppose the effects of 4EBP, growth factors phosphorylate 4EBP, reducing its affinity for eIF4E and permitting protein synthesis.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] While protein synthesis is globally regulated by modulating the expression of key initiation factors as well as the number of ribosomes, individual mRNAs can have different translation rates due to the presence of regulatory sequence elements.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] This has been shown to be important in a variety of settings including yeast meiosis and ethylene response in plants.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] In addition, recent work in yeast and humans suggest that evolutionary divergence in cis-regulatory sequences can impact translation regulation.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Additionally, RNA helicases such as DHX29 and Ded1/DDX3 participate in the process of translation initiation, especially for mRNAs with structured 5'UTRs.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The best-studied example of cap-independent translation initiation in eukaryotes uses the internal ribosome entry site (IRES).
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Unlike cap-dependent translation, cap-independent translation does not require a 5' cap to initiate scanning from the 5' end of the mRNA until the start codon.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome can localize to the start site by direct binding, initiation factors, and/or ITAFs (IRES trans-acting factors) bypassing the need to scan the entire 5' UTR.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] This method of translation is important in conditions that require the translation of specific mRNAs during cellular stress, when overall translation is reduced.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Examples include factors responding to apoptosis and stress-induced responses.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Elongation depends on elongation factors.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] At the end of the initiation step, the mRNA is positioned so that the next codon can be translated during the elongation stage of protein synthesis.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The initiator tRNA occupies the P site in the ribosome, and the A site is ready to receive an aminoacyl-tRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] During chain elongation, each additional amino acid is added to the nascent polypeptide chain in a three-step microcycle.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The steps in this microcycle are (1) positioning the correct aminoacyl-tRNA in the A site of the ribosome, which is brought into that site by eEF1, (2) forming the peptide bond, and (3) shifting the mRNA by one codon relative to the ribosome with the help of eEF2.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Eukaryotic mRNA precursors must be processed in the nucleus (e.g., capping, polyadenylation, splicing) in ribosomes before they are exported to the cytoplasm for translation.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Translation can also be affected by ribosomal pausing, which can trigger endonucleolytic attack of the tRNA, a process termed mRNA no-go decay.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Ribosomal pausing also aids co-translational folding of the nascent polypeptide on the ribosome, and delays protein translation while it is encoding tRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] This can trigger ribosomal frameshifting.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The last tRNA validated by the small ribosomal subunit (***accommodation***) transfers the amino acid.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] It carries to the large ribosomal subunit which binds it to one of the preceding admitted tRNA (***transpeptidation***).
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The ribosome then moves to the next mRNA codon to continue the process (***translocation***), creating an amino acid chain.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] In bacterial translation, and archaeal translation, translation occurs in the cytosol, where the ribosome binds to the mRNA.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] In eukaryotes, translation can occur in the cytoplasm and also across the membrane of the endoplasmic reticulum through a process called co-translational translocation.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Many types of transcribed RNA, such as tRNA, ribosomal RNA, and small nuclear RNA, do not undergo a translation into proteins.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Several antibiotics act by inhibiting translation.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] These include anisomycin, cycloheximide, chloramphenicol, tetracycline, streptomycin, erythromycin, and puromycin.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Prokaryotic ribosomes have a different structure from that of eukaryotic ribosomes, and thus antibiotics can specifically target bacterial infections without harming a eukaryotic host's cells.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Termination of elongation depends on the release factor eRF1 that recognizes all three stop codons.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] When a stop codon is reached, termination of the polypeptide occurs the ribosome is disassembled and the completed polypeptide is released. eRF3 is a ribosome-dependent GTPase that helps eRF1 release the completed polypeptide.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The human genome encodes a few genes whose mRNA stop codons are surprisingly leaky: In these genes, termination of translation is inefficient due to special RNA bases in the vicinity of the stop codon.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Leaky termination in these genes leads to translational readthrough of up to 10% of the stop codons of these genes.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Some of these genes encode functional protein domains in their readthrough extension so that new protein isoforms can arise.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] This process has been termed 'functional translational readthrough'.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] When the A site of the ribosome is occupied by a stop codon (UAA, UAG, or UGA) on the mRNA, creating the primary structure of a protein. tRNA usually cannot recognize or bind to stop codons.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Instead, the stop codon induces the binding of a release factor protein (RF1 & RF2) that prompts the disassembly of the entire ribosome/mRNA complex by the hydrolysis of the polypeptide chain from the peptidyl transferase center of the ribosome.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Drugs or special sequence motifs on the mRNA can change the ribosomal structure so that near-cognate tRNAs are bound to the stop codon instead of the release factors.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] In such cases of 'translational readthrough', translation continues until the ribosome encounters the next stop codon.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] When the synthesised protein is released the complex ribosome disassembles into its subunits for recycling.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The rate of error in synthesizing proteins has been estimated to be between 1 in 105 and 1 in 103 misincorporated amino acids, depending on the experimental conditions.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The rate of premature translation abandonment, instead, has been estimated to be of the order of magnitude of 10−4 events per translated codon.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Translation is one of the key energy consumers in cells, hence it is strictly regulated.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Numerous mechanisms have evolved that control and regulate translation in eukaryotes as well as prokaryotes.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Regulation of translation can impact the global rate of protein synthesis which is closely coupled to the metabolic and proliferative state of a cell.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Other methods such as toeprinting assay can also be used to determine the location of ribosomes of a particular mRNA in vitro, and footprints of other proteins regulating translation.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] To delve deeper into this intricate process, scientists typically use a technique known as ribosome profiling.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] This method enables researchers to take a snapshot of the translatome, showing which parts of the mRNA are being translated into proteins by ribosomes at a given time.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Ribosome profiling provides valuable insights into translation dynamics, revealing the complex interplay between gene sequence, mRNA structure, and translation regulation.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Expanding on this concept, single-cell ribosome profiling, is a technique that allows the study of the translation process at the resolution of individual cells.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Single-cell ribosome profiling has revealed that genetic differences and their subsequent expression as mRNAs can also impact translation rate in an RNA-specific manner.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Single-cell ribosome profiling has the potential to shed light on the heterogeneous nature of cells, leading to a more nuanced understanding of how translation regulation can impact cell behavior, metabolic state, and responsiveness to various stimuli or conditions.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] In some cells certain amino acids can be depleted and thus affect translation efficiency.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] For instance, activated T cells secrete interferon-γ which triggers intracellular tryptophan shortage by upregulating the indoleamine 2,3-dioxygenase 1 (IDO1) enzyme.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Despite tryptophan depletion, in-frame protein synthesis continues across tryptophan codons.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] This is achieved by incorporation of phenylalanine instead of tryptophan.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The resulting peptides are called W>F "substitutants".
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Such W>F substitutants are abundant in certain cancer types and have been associated with increased IDO1 expression.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Functionally, W>F substitutants can impair protein activity.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Translational control is critical for the development and survival of cancer.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Cancer cells must frequently regulate the translation phase of gene expression, though it is not fully understood why translation is targeted over steps like transcription.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] While cancer cells often have genetically altered translation factors, it is much more common for cancer cells to modify the levels of existing translation factors.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Several major oncogenic signaling pathways, including the RAS–MAPK, PI3K/AKT/mTOR, MYC, and WNT–β-catenin pathways, ultimately reprogram the genome via translation.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Cancer cells also control translation to adapt to cellular stress.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] During stress, the cell translates mRNAs that can mitigate the stress and promote survival.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] An example of this is the expression of AMPK in various cancers; its activation triggers a cascade that can ultimately allow the cancer to escape apoptosis (programmed cell death) triggered by nutrition deprivation.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Future cancer therapies may involve disrupting the translation machinery of the cell to counter the downstream effects of cancer.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The process of amino acid building to create protein in translation is a subject of various physic models for a long time starting from the first detailed kinetic models such as or others taking into account stochastic aspects of translation and using computer simulations.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Many chemical kinetics-based models of protein synthesis have been developed and analyzed in the last four decades.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Beyond chemical kinetics, various modeling formalisms such as Totally Asymmetric Simple Exclusion Process, Probabilistic Boolean Networks, Petri Nets and max-plus algebra have been applied to model the detailed kinetics of protein synthesis or some of its stages.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] A basic model of protein synthesis that takes into account all eight 'elementary' processes has been developed, following the paradigm that "useful models are simple and extendable".
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The simplest model *M0* is represented by the reaction kinetic mechanism (Figure M0).
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] It was generalised to include 40S, 60S and initiation factors (IF) binding (Figure M1').
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] It was extended further to include effect of microRNA on protein synthesis.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Most of models in this hierarchy can be solved analytically.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] These solutions were used to extract 'kinetic signatures' of different specific mechanisms of synthesis regulation.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] It is also possible to translate either by hand (for short sequences) or by computer (after first programming one appropriately, see section below); this allows biologists and chemists to draw out the primary amino acid sequence of the encoded protein on paper.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] First, convert each template DNA base to its RNA complement (note that the complement of A is now U), as shown below.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Note that the template strand of the DNA is the one the RNA is polymerized against; the other DNA strand would be the same as the RNA, but with thymine instead of uracil.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Then split the RNA into triplets (groups of three bases).
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Note that there are 3 translation "windows", or reading frames, depending on where you start reading the code.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Finally, use the table at Genetic code to translate the above into a structural formula as used in chemistry.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] This will give the primary structure of the protein.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] However, proteins tend to fold, depending in part on hydrophilic and hydrophobic segments along the chain.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Secondary structure can often still be guessed, but the proper tertiary structure is often very hard to determine.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] In order to determine the precise 3D structure and atomic interactions, Structural biology and several other Biophysics methods are used.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Whereas other aspects such as the 3D structure, called tertiary structure, of protein can only be predicted using sophisticated algorithms, the amino acid sequence, called primary structure, can be determined solely from the nucleic acid sequence with the aid of a translation table.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] There are many computer programs capable of translating a DNA/RNA sequence into a protein sequence.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Normally this is performed using the Standard Genetic Code, however, few programs can handle all the "special" cases, such as the use of the alternative initiation codons which are biologically significant.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] For instance, the rare alternative start codon CTG codes for Methionine when used as a start codon, and for Leucine in all other positions.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Example: Condensed translation table for the Standard Genetic Code (from the NCBI Taxonomy webpage).
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] The "Starts" row indicate three start codons, UUG, CUG, and the very common AUG.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] It also indicates the first amino acid residue when interpreted as a start: in this case it is all methionine.
[src:molecular-biology/translation-biology] Even when working with ordinary eukaryotic sequences such as the Yeast genome, it is often desired to be able to use alternative translation tables—namely for translation of the mitochondrial genes.
